44Ac 1:1 The first account I composed, Theophilus, about all that Jesus began to do and teach,
44Ac 1:2 until the day when He was taken up, after He had by the Holy Spirit given orders to the apostles whom He had chosen.
44Ac 1:3 To these He also presented Himself alive, after His suffering, by many convincing proofs, appearing to them over [a period of] forty days, and speaking of the things concerning the kingdom of God.
44Ac 1:4 And gathering them together, He commanded them not to leave Jerusalem, but to wait for what the Father had promised, "Which," [He said,] " you heard of from Me;
44Ac 1:5 for John baptized with water, but you shall be baptized with the Holy Spirit not many days from now. "
44Ac 1:6 And so when they had come together, they were asking Him, saying, " Lord, is it at this time You are restoring the kingdom to Israel? "
44Ac 1:7 He said to them, "It is not for you to know times or epochs which the Father has fixed by His own authority;
44Ac 1:8 but you shall receive power when the Holy Spirit has come upon you; and you shall be My witnesses both in Jerusalem, and in all Judea and Samaria, and even to the remotest part of the earth. "
44Ac 1:9 And after He had said these things, He was lifted up while they were looking on, and a cloud received Him out of their sight.
44Ac 1:10 And as they were gazing intently into the sky while He was departing, behold, two men in white clothing stood beside them;
44Ac 1:11 and they also said, "Men of Galilee, why do you stand looking into the sky? This Jesus, who has been taken up from you into heaven, will come in just the same way as you have watched Him go into heaven."
44Ac 1:12 Then they returned to Jerusalem from the mount called Olivet, which is near Jerusalem, a Sabbath day's journey away.
44Ac 1:13 And when they had entered, they went up to the upper room, where they were staying; that is, Peter and John and James and Andrew, Philip and Thomas, Bartholomew and Matthew, James [the son] of Alphaeus, and Simon the Zealot, and Judas [the son] of James.
44Ac 1:14 These all with one mind were continually devoting themselves to prayer, along with [the] women, and Mary the mother of Jesus, and with His brothers.
44Ac 1:15 And at this time Peter stood up in the midst of the brethren (a gathering of about one hundred and twenty persons was there together), and said,
44Ac 1:16 "Brethren, the Scripture had to be fulfilled, which the Holy Spirit foretold by the mouth of David concerning Judas, who became a guide to those who arrested Jesus.
44Ac 1:17 "For he was counted among us, and received his portion in this ministry."
44Ac 1:18 (Now this man acquired a field with the price of his wickedness; and falling headlong, he burst open in the middle and all his bowels gushed out.
44Ac 1:19 And it became known to all who were living in Jerusalem; so that in their own language that field was called Hakeldama, that is, Field of Blood.)
44Ac 1:20 "For it is written in the book of Psalms, 'LET HIS HOMESTEAD BE MADE DESOLATE, AND LET NO MAN DWELL IN IT'; and, 'HIS OFFICE LET ANOTHER MAN TAKE.'
44Ac 1:21 "It is therefore necessary that of the men who have accompanied us all the time that the Lord Jesus went in and out among us--
44Ac 1:22 beginning with the baptism of John, until the day that He was taken up from us-- one of these should become a witness with us of His resurrection. "
44Ac 1:23 And they put forward two men, Joseph called Barsabbas (who was also called Justus), and Matthias.
44Ac 1:24 And they prayed, and said, "Thou, Lord, who knowest the hearts of all men, show which one of these two Thou hast chosen
44Ac 1:25 to occupy this ministry and apostleship from which Judas turned aside to go to his own place. "
44Ac 1:26 And they drew lots for them, and the lot fell to Matthias; and he was numbered with the eleven apostles.
44Ac 2:1 And when the day of Pentecost had come, they were all together in one place.
44Ac 2:2 And suddenly there came from heaven a noise like a violent, rushing wind, and it filled the whole house where they were sitting.
44Ac 2:3 And there appeared to them tongues as of fire distributing themselves, and they rested on each one of them.
44Ac 2:4 And they were all filled with the Holy Spirit and began to speak with other tongues, as the Spirit was giving them utterance.
44Ac 2:5 Now there were Jews living in Jerusalem, devout men, from every nation under heaven.
44Ac 2:6 And when this sound occurred, the multitude came together, and were bewildered, because they were each one hearing them speak in his own language.
44Ac 2:7 And they were amazed and marveled, saying, "Why, are not all these who are speaking Galileans?
44Ac 2:8 "And how is it that we each hear [them] in our own language to which we were born?
44Ac 2:9 "Parthians and Medes and Elamites, and residents of Mesopotamia, Judea and Cappadocia, Pontus and Asia,
44Ac 2:10 Phrygia and Pamphylia, Egypt and the districts of Libya around Cyrene, and visitors from Rome, both Jews and proselytes,
44Ac 2:11 Cretans and Arabs-- we hear them in our [own] tongues speaking of the mighty deeds of God. "
44Ac 2:12 And they all continued in amazement and great perplexity, saying to one another, "What does this mean?"
44Ac 2:13 But others were mocking and saying, "They are full of sweet wine."
44Ac 2:14 But Peter, taking his stand with the eleven, raised his voice and declared to them： "Men of Judea, and all you who live in Jerusalem, let this be known to you, and give heed to my words.
44Ac 2:15 "For these men are not drunk, as you suppose, for it is [only] the third hour of the day;
44Ac 2:16 but this is what was spoken of through the prophet Joel：
44Ac 2:17 'AND IT SHALL BE IN THE LAST DAYS,' God says, 'THAT I WILL POUR FORTH OF MY SPIRIT UPON ALL MANKIND; AND YOUR SONS AND YOUR DAUGHTERS SHALL PROPHESY, AND YOUR YOUNG MEN SHALL SEE VISIONS, AND YOUR OLD MEN SHALL DREAM DREAMS;
44Ac 2:18 EVEN UPON MY BONDSLAVES, BOTH MEN AND WOMEN, I WILL IN THOSE DAYS POUR FORTH OF MY SPIRIT And they shall prophesy.
44Ac 2:19 'AND I WILL GRANT WONDERS IN THE SKY ABOVE, AND SIGNS ON THE EARTH BENEATH, BLOOD, AND FIRE, AND VAPOR OF SMOKE.
44Ac 2:20 'THE SUN SHALL BE TURNED INTO DARKNESS, AND THE MOON INTO BLOOD, BEFORE THE GREAT AND GLORIOUS DAY OF THE LORD SHALL COME.
44Ac 2:21 'AND IT SHALL BE, THAT EVERYONE WHO CALLS ON THE NAME OF THE LORD SHALL BE SAVED.'
44Ac 2:22 "Men of Israel, listen to these words： Jesus the Nazarene, a man attested to you by God with miracles and wonders and signs which God performed through Him in your midst, just as you yourselves know--
44Ac 2:23 this [Man], delivered up by the predetermined plan and foreknowledge of God, you nailed to a cross by the hands of godless men and put [Him] to death.
44Ac 2:24 "And God raised Him up again, putting an end to the agony of death, since it was impossible for Him to be held in its power.
44Ac 2:25 "For David says of Him, 'I WAS ALWAYS BEHOLDING THE LORD IN MY PRESENCE; FOR HE IS AT MY RIGHT HAND, THAT I MAY NOT BE SHAKEN.
44Ac 2:26 'THEREFORE MY HEART WAS GLAD AND MY TONGUE EXULTED; MOREOVER MY FLESH ALSO WILL ABIDE IN HOPE;
44Ac 2:27 BECAUSE THOU WILT NOT ABANDON MY SOUL TO HADES, NOR ALLOW THY HOLY ONE TO UNDERGO DECAY.
44Ac 2:28 'THOU HAST MADE KNOWN TO ME THE WAYS OF LIFE; THOU WILT MAKE ME FULL OF GLADNESS WITH THY PRESENCE.'
44Ac 2:29 "Brethren, I may confidently say to you regarding the patriarch David that he both died and was buried, and his tomb is with us to this day.
44Ac 2:30 "And so, because he was a prophet, and knew that GOD HAD SWORN TO HIM WITH AN OATH TO SEAT [one] OF HIS DESCENDANTS UPON HIS THRONE,
44Ac 2:31 he looked ahead and spoke of the resurrection of the Christ, that HE WAS NEITHER ABANDONED TO HADES, NOR DID His flesh SUFFER DECAY .
44Ac 2:32 "This Jesus God raised up again, to which we are all witnesses.
44Ac 2:33 "Therefore having been exalted to the right hand of God, and having received from the Father the promise of the Holy Spirit, He has poured forth this which you both see and hear.
44Ac 2:34 "For it was not David who ascended into heaven, but he himself says： 'THE LORD SAID TO MY LORD," SIT AT MY RIGHT HAND,
44Ac 2:35 UNTIL I MAKE THINE ENEMIES A FOOTSTOOL FOR THY FEET. "'
44Ac 2:36 "Therefore let all the house of Israel know for certain that God has made Him both Lord and Christ-- this Jesus whom you crucified."
44Ac 2:37 Now when they heard [this], they were pierced to the heart, and said to Peter and the rest of the apostles, "Brethren, what shall we do?"
44Ac 2:38 And Peter [said] to them, "Repent, and let each of you be baptized in the name of Jesus Christ for the forgiveness of your sins; and you shall receive the gift of the Holy Spirit.
44Ac 2:39 "For the promise is for you and your children, and for all who are far off, as many as the Lord our God shall call to Himself."
44Ac 2:40 And with many other words he solemnly testified and kept on exhorting them, saying, "Be saved from this perverse generation!"
44Ac 2:41 So then, those who had received his word were baptized; and there were added that day about three thousand souls.
44Ac 2:42 And they were continually devoting themselves to the apostles' teaching and to fellowship, to the breaking of bread and to prayer.
44Ac 2:43 And everyone kept feeling a sense of awe; and many wonders and signs were taking place through the apostles.
44Ac 2:44 And all those who had believed were together, and had all things in common;
44Ac 2:45 and they [began] selling their property and possessions, and were sharing them with all, as anyone might have need.
44Ac 2:46 And day by day continuing with one mind in the temple, and breaking bread from house to house, they were taking their meals together with gladness and sincerity of heart,
44Ac 2:47 praising God, and having favor with all the people. And the Lord was adding to their number day by day those who were being saved.
44Ac 3:1 Now Peter and John were going up to the temple at the ninth [hour,] the hour of prayer.
44Ac 3:2 And a certain man who had been lame from his mother's womb was being carried along, whom they used to set down every day at the gate of the temple which is called Beautiful, in order to beg alms of those who were entering the temple.
44Ac 3:3 And when he saw Peter and John about to go into the temple, he [began] asking to receive alms.
44Ac 3:4 And Peter, along with John, fixed his gaze upon him and said, "Look at us!"
44Ac 3:5 And he [began] to give them his attention, expecting to receive something from them.
44Ac 3:6 But Peter said, "I do not possess silver and gold, but what I do have I give to you： In the name of Jesus Christ the Nazarene-- walk!"
44Ac 3:7 And seizing him by the right hand, he raised him up; and immediately his feet and his ankles were strengthened.
44Ac 3:8 And with a leap, he stood upright and [began] to walk; and he entered the temple with them, walking and leaping and praising God.
44Ac 3:9 And all the people saw him walking and praising God;
44Ac 3:10 and they were taking note of him as being the one who used to sit at the Beautiful Gate of the temple to [beg] alms, and they were filled with wonder and amazement at what had happened to him.
44Ac 3:11 And while he was clinging to Peter and John, all the people ran together to them at the so-called portico of Solomon, full of amazement.
44Ac 3:12 But when Peter saw [this], he replied to the people, "Men of Israel, why do you marvel at this, or why do you gaze at us, as if by our own power or piety we had made him walk?
44Ac 3:13 "The God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, the God of our fathers, has glorified His servant Jesus, [the one] whom you delivered up, and disowned in the presence of Pilate, when he had decided to release Him.
44Ac 3:14 "But you disowned the Holy and Righteous One, and asked for a murderer to be granted to you,
44Ac 3:15 but put to death the Prince of life, [the one] whom God raised from the dead, [a fact] to which we are witnesses.
44Ac 3:16 "And on the basis of faith in His name, [it is] the name of Jesus which has strengthened this man whom you see and know; and the faith which [ comes] through Him has given him this perfect health in the presence of you all.
44Ac 3:17 "And now, brethren, I know that you acted in ignorance, just as your rulers did also.
44Ac 3:18 "But the things which God announced beforehand by the mouth of all the prophets, that His Christ should suffer, He has thus fulfilled.
44Ac 3:19 "Repent therefore and return, that your sins may be wiped away, in order that times of refreshing may come from the presence of the Lord;
44Ac 3:20 and that He may send Jesus, the Christ appointed for you,
44Ac 3:21 whom heaven must receive until [the] period of restoration of all things about which God spoke by the mouth of His holy prophets from ancient time.
44Ac 3:22 "Moses said, 'THE LORD GOD SHALL RAISE UP FOR YOU A PROPHET LIKE ME FROM YOUR BRETHREN; TO HIM YOU SHALL GIVE HEED in everything He says to you.
44Ac 3:23 'And it shall be that every soul that does not heed that prophet shall be utterly destroyed from among the people.'
44Ac 3:24 "And likewise, all the prophets who have spoken, from Samuel and [his] successors onward, also announced these days.
44Ac 3:25 "It is you who are the sons of the prophets, and of the covenant which God made with your fathers, saying to Abraham, 'AND IN YOUR SEED ALL THE FAMILIES OF THE EARTH SHALL BE BLESSED.'
44Ac 3:26 "For you first, God raised up His Servant, and sent Him to bless you by turning every one [of you] from your wicked ways."
44Ac 4:1 And as they were speaking to the people, the priests and the captain of the temple [guard,] and the Sadducees, came upon them,
44Ac 4:2 being greatly disturbed because they were teaching the people and proclaiming in Jesus the resurrection from the dead.
44Ac 4:3 And they laid hands on them, and put them in jail until the next day, for it was already evening.
44Ac 4:4 But many of those who had heard the message believed; and the number of the men came to be about five thousand.
44Ac 4:5 And it came about on the next day, that their rulers and elders and scribes were gathered together in Jerusalem;
44Ac 4:6 and Annas the high priest [was there,] and Caiaphas and John and Alexander, and all who were of high-priestly descent.
44Ac 4:7 And when they had placed them in the center, they [began to] inquire, "By what power, or in what name, have you done this?"
44Ac 4:8 Then Peter, filled with the Holy Spirit, said to them, "Rulers and elders of the people,
44Ac 4:9 if we are on trial today for a benefit done to a sick man, as to how this man has been made well,
44Ac 4:10 let it be known to all of you, and to all the people of Israel, that by the name of Jesus Christ the Nazarene, whom you crucified, whom God raised from the dead-- by this [name] this man stands here before you in good health.
44Ac 4:11 "He is the STONE WHICH WAS REJECTED by you, THE BUILDERS, [but] WHICH BECAME THE VERY CORNER [stone.]
44Ac 4:12 "And there is salvation in no one else; for there is no other name under heaven that has been given among men, by which we must be saved."
44Ac 4:13 Now as they observed the confidence of Peter and John, and understood that they were uneducated and untrained men, they were marveling, and [began] to recognize them as having been with Jesus.
44Ac 4:14 And seeing the man who had been healed standing with them, they had nothing to say in reply.
44Ac 4:15 But when they had ordered them to go aside out of the Council, they [began] to confer with one another,
44Ac 4:16 saying, "What shall we do with these men? For the fact that a noteworthy miracle has taken place through them is apparent to all who live in Jerusalem, and we cannot deny it.
44Ac 4:17 "But in order that it may not spread any further among the people, let us warn them to speak no more to any man in this name."
44Ac 4:18 And when they had summoned them, they commanded them not to speak or teach at all in the name of Jesus.
44Ac 4:19 But Peter and John answered and said to them, "Whether it is right in the sight of God to give heed to you rather than to God, you be the judge;
44Ac 4:20 for we cannot stop speaking what we have seen and heard. "
44Ac 4:21 And when they had threatened them further, they let them go (finding no basis on which they might punish them) on account of the people, because they were all glorifying God for what had happened;
44Ac 4:22 for the man was more than forty years old on whom this miracle of healing had been performed.
44Ac 4:23 And when they had been released, they went to their own [companions,] and reported all that the chief priests and the elders had said to them.
44Ac 4:24 And when they heard [this,] they lifted their voices to God with one accord and said, "O Lord, it is Thou who DIDST MAKE THE HEAVEN AND THE EARTH AND THE SEA, AND ALL THAT IS IN THEM,
44Ac 4:25 who by the Holy Spirit, [through] the mouth of our father David Thy servant, didst say, 'WHY DID THE GENTILES RAGE, AND THE PEOPLES DEVISE FUTILE THINGS?
44Ac 4:26 'THE KINGS OF THE EARTH TOOK THEIR STAND, AND THE RULERS WERE GATHERED TOGETHER AGAINST THE LORD, AND AGAINST HIS CHRIST.'
44Ac 4:27 "For truly in this city there were gathered together against Thy holy servant Jesus, whom Thou didst anoint, both Herod and Pontius Pilate, along with the Gentiles and the peoples of Israel,
44Ac 4:28 to do whatever Thy hand and Thy purpose predestined to occur.
44Ac 4:29 "And now, Lord, take note of their threats, and grant that Thy bond-servants may speak Thy word with all confidence,
44Ac 4:30 while Thou dost extend Thy hand to heal, and signs and wonders take place through the name of Thy holy servant Jesus. "
44Ac 4:31 And when they had prayed, the place where they had gathered together was shaken, and they were all filled with the Holy Spirit, and [began] to speak the word of God with boldness.
44Ac 4:32 And the congregation of those who believed were of one heart and soul; and not one [of them] claimed that anything belonging to him was his own; but all things were common property to them.
44Ac 4:33 And with great power the apostles were giving witness to the resurrection of the Lord Jesus, and abundant grace was upon them all.
44Ac 4:34 For there was not a needy person among them, for all who were owners of land or houses would sell them and bring the proceeds of the sales,
44Ac 4:35 and lay them at the apostles' feet; and they would be distributed to each, as any had need.
44Ac 4:36 And Joseph, a Levite of Cyprian birth, who was also called Barnabas by the apostles (which translated means, Son of Encouragement),
44Ac 4:37 and who owned a tract of land, sold it and brought the money and laid it at the apostles' feet.
44Ac 5:1 But a certain man named Ananias, with his wife Sapphira, sold a piece of property,
44Ac 5:2 and kept back [some] of the price for himself, with his wife's full knowledge, and bringing a portion of it, he laid it at the apostles' feet.
44Ac 5:3 But Peter said, "Ananias, why has Satan filled your heart to lie to the Holy Spirit, and to keep back [some] of the price of the land?
44Ac 5:4 "While it remained [unsold,] did it not remain your own? And after it was sold, was it not under your control? Why is it that you have conceived this deed in your heart? You have not lied to men, but to God."
44Ac 5:5 And as he heard these words, Ananias fell down and breathed his last; and great fear came upon all who heard of it.
44Ac 5:6 And the young men arose and covered him up, and after carrying him out, they buried him.
44Ac 5:7 Now there elapsed an interval of about three hours, and his wife came in, not knowing what had happened.
44Ac 5:8 And Peter responded to her, "Tell me whether you sold the land for such and such a price?" And she said, "Yes, that was the price."
44Ac 5:9 Then Peter [said] to her, "Why is it that you have agreed together to put the Spirit of the Lord to the test? Behold, the feet of those who have buried your husband are at the door, and they shall carry you out [as well]."
44Ac 5:10 And she fell immediately at his feet, and breathed her last; and the young men came in and found her dead, and they carried her out and buried her beside her husband.
44Ac 5:11 And great fear came upon the whole church, and upon all who heard of these things.
44Ac 5:12 And at the hands of the apostles many signs and wonders were taking place among the people; and they were all with one accord in Solomon's portico.
44Ac 5:13 But none of the rest dared to associate with them; however, the people held them in high esteem.
44Ac 5:14 And all the more believers in the Lord, multitudes of men and women, were constantly added to [their number];
44Ac 5:15 to such an extent that they even carried the sick out into the streets, and laid them on cots and pallets, so that when Peter came by, at least his shadow might fall on any one of them.
44Ac 5:16 And also the people from the cities in the vicinity of Jerusalem were coming together, bringing people who were sick or afflicted with unclean spirits; and they were all being healed.
44Ac 5:17 But the high priest rose up, along with all his associates (that is the sect of the Sadducees), and they were filled with jealousy;
44Ac 5:18 and they laid hands on the apostles, and put them in a public jail.
44Ac 5:19 But an angel of the Lord during the night opened the gates of the prison, and taking them out he said,
44Ac 5:20 "Go your way, stand and speak to the people in the temple the whole message of this Life."
44Ac 5:21 And upon hearing [this,] they entered into the temple about daybreak, and [began] to teach. Now when the high priest and his associates had come, they called the Council together, even all the Senate of the sons of Israel, and sent [orders] to the prison house for them to be brought.
44Ac 5:22 But the officers who came did not find them in the prison; and they returned, and reported back,
44Ac 5:23 saying, "We found the prison house locked quite securely and the guards standing at the doors; but when we had opened up, we found no one inside."
44Ac 5:24 Now when the captain of the temple [guard] and the chief priests heard these words, they were greatly perplexed about them as to what would come of this.
44Ac 5:25 But someone came and reported to them, "Behold, the men whom you put in prison are standing in the temple and teaching the people!"
44Ac 5:26 Then the captain went along with the officers and [proceeded] to bring them [back] without violence (for they were afraid of the people, lest they should be stoned).
44Ac 5:27 And when they had brought them, they stood them before the Council. And the high priest questioned them,
44Ac 5:28 saying, "We gave you strict orders not to continue teaching in this name, and behold, you have filled Jerusalem with your teaching, and intend to bring this man's blood upon us."
44Ac 5:29 But Peter and the apostles answered and said, "We must obey God rather than men.
44Ac 5:30 "The God of our fathers raised up Jesus, whom you had put to death by hanging Him on a cross.
44Ac 5:31 "He is the one whom God exalted to His right hand as a Prince and a Savior, to grant repentance to Israel, and forgiveness of sins.
44Ac 5:32 "And we are witnesses of these things; and [so is] the Holy Spirit, whom God has given to those who obey Him."
44Ac 5:33 But when they heard this, they were cut to the quick and were intending to slay them.
44Ac 5:34 But a certain Pharisee named Gamaliel, a teacher of the Law, respected by all the people, stood up in the Council and gave orders to put the men outside for a short time.
44Ac 5:35 And he said to them, "Men of Israel, take care what you propose to do with these men.
44Ac 5:36 "For some time ago Theudas rose up, claiming to be somebody; and a group of about four hundred men joined up with him. And he was slain; and all who followed him were dispersed and came to nothing.
44Ac 5:37 "After this man Judas of Galilee rose up in the days of the census, and drew away [some] people after him, he too perished, and all those who followed him were scattered.
44Ac 5:38 "And so in the present case, I say to you, stay away from these men and let them alone, for if this plan or action should be of men, it will be overthrown;
44Ac 5:39 but if it is of God, you will not be able to overthrow them; or else you may even be found fighting against God. "
44Ac 5:40 And they took his advice; and after calling the apostles in, they flogged them and ordered them to speak no more in the name of Jesus, and [then] released them.
44Ac 5:41 So they went on their way from the presence of the Council, rejoicing that they had been considered worthy to suffer shame for [His] name.
44Ac 5:42 And every day, in the temple and from house to house, they kept right on teaching and preaching Jesus [as] the Christ.
44Ac 6:1 Now at this time while the disciples were increasing [in number,] a complaint arose on the part of the Hellenistic [Jews] against the [native] Hebrews, because their widows were being overlooked in the daily serving [of food.]
44Ac 6:2 And the twelve summoned the congregation of the disciples and said, " It is not desirable for us to neglect the word of God in order to serve tables.
44Ac 6:3 "But select from among you, brethren, seven men of good reputation, full of the Spirit and of wisdom, whom we may put in charge of this task.
44Ac 6:4 "But we will devote ourselves to prayer, and to the ministry of the word."
44Ac 6:5 And the statement found approval with the whole congregation; and they chose Stephen, a man full of faith and of the Holy Spirit, and Philip, Prochorus, Nicanor, Timon, Parmenas and Nicolas, a proselyte from Antioch.
44Ac 6:6 And these they brought before the apostles; and after praying, they laid their hands on them.
44Ac 6:7 And the word of God kept on spreading; and the number of the disciples continued to increase greatly in Jerusalem, and a great many of the priests were becoming obedient to the faith.
44Ac 6:8 And Stephen, full of grace and power, was performing great wonders and signs among the people.
44Ac 6:9 But some men from what was called the Synagogue of the Freedmen, [including] both Cyrenians and Alexandrians, and some from Cilicia and Asia, rose up and argued with Stephen.
44Ac 6:10 And [yet] they were unable to cope with the wisdom and the Spirit with which he was speaking.
44Ac 6:11 Then they secretly induced men to say, "We have heard him speak blasphemous words against Moses and [against] God."
44Ac 6:12 And they stirred up the people, the elders and the scribes, and they came upon him and dragged him away, and brought him before the Council.
44Ac 6:13 And they put forward false witnesses who said, "This man incessantly speaks against this holy place, and the Law;
44Ac 6:14 for we have heard him say that this Nazarene, Jesus, will destroy this place and alter the customs which Moses handed down to us. "
44Ac 6:15 And fixing their gaze on him, all who were sitting in the Council saw his face like the face of an angel.
44Ac 7:1 And the high priest said, "Are these things so?"
44Ac 7:2 And he said, "Hear me, brethren and fathers! The God of glory appeared to our father Abraham when he was in Mesopotamia, before he lived in Haran,
44Ac 7:3 and said to him, 'DEPART FROM YOUR COUNTRY AND YOUR RELATIVES, AND COME INTO THE LAND THAT I WILL SHOW YOU.'
44Ac 7:4 "Then he departed from the land of the Chaldeans, and settled in Haran. And from there, after his father died, [God] removed him into this country in which you are now living.
44Ac 7:5 "And He gave him no inheritance in it, not even a foot of ground; and [yet,] even when he had no child, He promised that HE WOULD GIVE IT TO HIM AS A POSSESSION, AND TO HIS OFFSPRING AFTER HIM.
44Ac 7:6 "But God spoke to this effect, that his OFFSPRING WOULD BE ALIENS IN A FOREIGN LAND, AND THAT THEY WOULD BE ENSLAVED AND MISTREATED FOR FOUR HUNDRED YEARS.
44Ac 7:7 "'AND WHATEVER NATION TO WHICH THEY SHALL BE IN BONDAGE I MYSELF WILL JUDGE,' said God, 'AND AFTER THAT THEY WILL COME OUT AND SERVE ME IN THIS PLACE.'
44Ac 7:8 "And He gave him the covenant of circumcision; and so [Abraham] became the father of Isaac, and circumcised him on the eighth day; and Isaac [became the father of] Jacob, and Jacob [of] the twelve patriarchs.
44Ac 7:9 "And the patriarchs became jealous of Joseph and sold him into Egypt. And [yet] God was with him,
44Ac 7:10 and rescued him from all his afflictions, and granted him favor and wisdom in the sight of Pharaoh, king of Egypt; and he made him governor over Egypt and all his household.
44Ac 7:11 "Now a famine came over all Egypt and Canaan, and great affliction [ with it;] and our fathers could find no food.
44Ac 7:12 "But when Jacob heard that there was grain in Egypt, he sent our fathers [there] the first time.
44Ac 7:13 "And on the second [visit] Joseph made himself known to his brothers, and Joseph's family was disclosed to Pharaoh.
44Ac 7:14 "And Joseph sent [word] and invited Jacob his father and all his relatives to come to him, seventy-five persons [in all.]
44Ac 7:15 "And Jacob went down to Egypt and [there] passed away, he and our fathers.
44Ac 7:16 "And [from there] they were removed to Shechem, and laid in the tomb which Abraham had purchased for a sum of money from the sons of Hamor in Shechem.
44Ac 7:17 "But as the time of the promise was approaching which God had assured to Abraham, the people increased and multiplied in Egypt,
44Ac 7:18 until THERE AROSE ANOTHER KING OVER EGYPT WHO KNEW NOTHING ABOUT JOSEPH.
44Ac 7:19 "It was he who took shrewd advantage of our race, and mistreated our fathers so that they would expose their infants and they would not survive.
44Ac 7:20 "And it was at this time that Moses was born; and he was lovely in the sight of God; and he was nurtured three months in his father's home.
44Ac 7:21 "And after he had been exposed, Pharaoh's daughter took him away, and nurtured him as her own son.
44Ac 7:22 "And Moses was educated in all the learning of the Egyptians, and he was a man of power in words and deeds.
44Ac 7:23 "But when he was approaching the age of forty, it entered his mind to visit his brethren, the sons of Israel.
44Ac 7:24 "And when he saw one [of them] being treated unjustly, he defended him and took vengeance for the oppressed by striking down the Egyptian.
44Ac 7:25 "And he supposed that his brethren understood that God was granting them deliverance through him; but they did not understand.
44Ac 7:26 "And on the following day he appeared to them as they were fighting together, and he tried to reconcile them in peace, saying, 'Men, you are brethren, why do you injure one another?'
44Ac 7:27 "But the one who was injuring his neighbor pushed him away, saying, ' WHO MADE YOU A RULER AND JUDGE OVER US?
44Ac 7:28 'YOU DO NOT MEAN TO KILL ME AS YOU KILLED THE EGYPTIAN YESTERDAY, DO YOU?'
44Ac 7:29 "And at this remark MOSES FLED, AND BECAME AN ALIEN IN THE LAND OF MIDIAN, where he became the father of two sons.
44Ac 7:30 "And after forty years had passed, AN ANGEL APPEARED TO HIM IN THE WILDERNESS OF MOUNT Sinai, IN THE FLAME OF A BURNING THORN BUSH.
44Ac 7:31 "And when Moses saw it, he [began] to marvel at the sight; and as he approached to look [more] closely, there came the voice of the Lord：
44Ac 7:32 'I AM THE GOD OF YOUR FATHERS, THE GOD OF ABRAHAM AND ISAAC AND JACOB.' And Moses shook with fear and would not venture to look.
44Ac 7:33 "BUT THE LORD SAID TO HIM, 'TAKE OFF THE SANDALS FROM YOUR FEET, FOR THE PLACE ON WHICH YOU ARE STANDING IS HOLY GROUND.
44Ac 7:34 'I HAVE CERTAINLY SEEN THE OPPRESSION OF MY PEOPLE IN EGYPT, AND HAVE HEARD THEIR GROANS, AND I HAVE COME DOWN TO DELIVER THEM; COME NOW, AND I WILL SEND YOU TO EGYPT.'
44Ac 7:35 "This Moses whom they disowned, saying, 'WHO MADE YOU A RULER AND A JUDGE?' is the one whom God sent [to be] both a ruler and a deliverer with the help of the angel who appeared to him in the thorn bush.
44Ac 7:36 "This man led them out, performing wonders and signs in the land of Egypt and in the Red Sea and in the wilderness for forty years.
44Ac 7:37 "This is the Moses who said to the sons of Israel, 'GOD SHALL RAISE UP FOR YOU A PROPHET LIKE ME FROM YOUR BRETHREN.'
44Ac 7:38 "This is the one who was in the congregation in the wilderness together with the angel who was speaking to him on Mount Sinai, and [who was] with our fathers; and he received living oracles to pass on to you.
44Ac 7:39 "And our fathers were unwilling to be obedient to him, but repudiated him and in their hearts turned back to Egypt,
44Ac 7:40 SAYING TO AARON, 'MAKE FOR US GODS WHO WILL GO BEFORE US; FOR THIS MOSES WHO LED US OUT OF THE LAND OF EGYPT-- WE DO NOT KNOW WHAT HAPPENED TO HIM.'
44Ac 7:41 "And at that time they made a calf and brought a sacrifice to the idol, and were rejoicing in the works of their hands.
44Ac 7:42 "But God turned away and delivered them up to serve the host of heaven; as it is written in the book of the prophets, 'IT WAS NOT TO ME THAT YOU OFFERED VICTIMS AND SACRIFICES FORTY YEARS IN THE WILDERNESS, WAS IT, O HOUSE OF ISRAEL?
44Ac 7:43 'YOU ALSO TOOK ALONG THE TABERNACLE OF MOLOCH AND THE STAR OF THE GOD ROMPHA, THE IMAGES WHICH YOU MADE TO WORSHIP THEM. I ALSO WILL REMOVE YOU BEYOND BABYLON.'
44Ac 7:44 "Our fathers had the tabernacle of testimony in the wilderness, just as He who spoke to Moses directed [him] to make it according to the pattern which he had seen.
44Ac 7:45 "And having received it in their turn, our fathers brought it in with Joshua upon dispossessing the nations whom God drove out before our fathers, until the time of David.
44Ac 7:46 "And [David] found favor in God's sight, and asked that he might find a dwelling place for the God of Jacob.
44Ac 7:47 "But it was Solomon who built a house for Him.
44Ac 7:48 "However, the Most High does not dwell in [houses] made by [human] hands; as the prophet says：
44Ac 7:49 'HEAVEN IS MY THRONE, AND EARTH IS THE FOOTSTOOL OF MY FEET; WHAT KIND OF HOUSE WILL YOU BUILD FOR ME ?'says the Lord; 'OR WHAT PLACE IS THERE FOR MY REPOSE ?
44Ac 7:50 'WAS IT NOT MY HAND WHICH MADE ALL THESE THINGS?'
44Ac 7:51 "You men who are stiff-necked and uncircumcised in heart and ears are always resisting the Holy Spirit; you are doing just as your fathers did.
44Ac 7:52 "Which one of the prophets did your fathers not persecute? And they killed those who had previously announced the coming of the Righteous One, whose betrayers and murderers you have now become;
44Ac 7:53 you who received the law as ordained by angels, and [yet] did not keep it. "
44Ac 7:54 Now when they heard this, they were cut to the quick, and they [began] gnashing their teeth at him.
44Ac 7:55 But being full of the Holy Spirit, he gazed intently into heaven and saw the glory of God, and Jesus standing at the right hand of God;
44Ac 7:56 and he said, "Behold, I see the heavens opened up and the Son of Man standing at the right hand of God."
44Ac 7:57 But they cried out with a loud voice, and covered their ears, and they rushed upon him with one impulse.
44Ac 7:58 And when they had driven him out of the city, they [began] stoning [ him,] and the witnesses laid aside their robes at the feet of a young man named Saul.
44Ac 7:59 And they went on stoning Stephen as he called upon [the Lord] and said, "Lord Jesus, receive my spirit!"
44Ac 7:60 And falling on his knees, he cried out with a loud voice, "Lord, do not hold this sin against them!" And having said this, he fell asleep.
44Ac 8:1 And Saul was in hearty agreement with putting him to death. And on that day a great persecution arose against the church in Jerusalem; and they were all scattered throughout the regions of Judea and Samaria, except the apostles.
44Ac 8:2 And [some] devout men buried Stephen, and made loud lamentation over him.
44Ac 8:3 But Saul [began] ravaging the church, entering house after house; and dragging off men and women, he would put them in prison.
44Ac 8:4 Therefore, those who had been scattered went about preaching the word.
44Ac 8:5 And Philip went down to the city of Samaria and [began] proclaiming Christ to them.
44Ac 8:6 And the multitudes with one accord were giving attention to what was said by Philip, as they heard and saw the signs which he was performing.
44Ac 8:7 For [in the case of] many who had unclean spirits, they were coming out [of them] shouting with a loud voice; and many who had been paralyzed and lame were healed.
44Ac 8:8 And there was much rejoicing in that city.
44Ac 8:9 Now there was a certain man named Simon, who formerly was practicing magic in the city, and astonishing the people of Samaria, claiming to be someone great;
44Ac 8:10 and they all, from smallest to greatest, were giving attention to him, saying, "This man is what is called the Great Power of God."
44Ac 8:11 And they were giving him attention because he had for a long time astonished them with his magic arts.
44Ac 8:12 But when they believed Philip preaching the good news about the kingdom of God and the name of Jesus Christ, they were being baptized, men and women alike.
44Ac 8:13 And even Simon himself believed; and after being baptized, he continued on with Philip; and as he observed signs and great miracles taking place, he was constantly amazed.
44Ac 8:14 Now when the apostles in Jerusalem heard that Samaria had received the word of God, they sent them Peter and John,
44Ac 8:15 who came down and prayed for them, that they might receive the Holy Spirit.
44Ac 8:16 For He had not yet fallen upon any of them; they had simply been baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus.
44Ac 8:17 Then they [began] laying their hands on them, and they were receiving the Holy Spirit.
44Ac 8:18 Now when Simon saw that the Spirit was bestowed through the laying on of the apostles' hands, he offered them money,
44Ac 8:19 saying, "Give this authority to me as well, so that everyone on whom I lay my hands may receive the Holy Spirit."
44Ac 8:20 But Peter said to him, "May your silver perish with you, because you thought you could obtain the gift of God with money!
44Ac 8:21 "You have no part or portion in this matter, for your heart is not right before God.
44Ac 8:22 "Therefore repent of this wickedness of yours, and pray the Lord that if possible, the intention of your heart may be forgiven you.
44Ac 8:23 "For I see that you are in the gall of bitterness and in the bondage of iniquity."
44Ac 8:24 But Simon answered and said, "Pray to the Lord for me yourselves, so that nothing of what you have said may come upon me."
44Ac 8:25 And so, when they had solemnly testified and spoken the word of the Lord, they started back to Jerusalem, and were preaching the gospel to many villages of the Samaritans.
44Ac 8:26 But an angel of the Lord spoke to Philip saying, "Arise and go south to the road that descends from Jerusalem to Gaza." (This is a desert [ road].)
44Ac 8:27 And he arose and went; and behold, there was an Ethiopian eunuch, a court official of Candace, queen of the Ethiopians, who was in charge of all her treasure; and he had come to Jerusalem to worship.
44Ac 8:28 And he was returning and sitting in his chariot, and was reading the prophet Isaiah.
44Ac 8:29 And the Spirit said to Philip, "Go up and join this chariot."
44Ac 8:30 And when Philip had run up, he heard him reading Isaiah the prophet, and said, "Do you understand what you are reading?"
44Ac 8:31 And he said, "Well, how could I, unless someone guides me?" And he invited Philip to come up and sit with him.
44Ac 8:32 Now the passage of Scripture which he was reading was this： "HE WAS LED AS A SHEEP TO SLAUGHTER; AND AS A LAMB BEFORE ITS SHEARER IS SILENT, SO HE DOES NOT OPEN HIS MOUTH.
44Ac 8:33 "IN HUMILIATION HIS JUDGMENT WAS TAKEN AWAY; WHO SHALL RELATE HIS GENERATION? FOR HIS LIFE IS REMOVED FROM THE EARTH."
44Ac 8:34 And the eunuch answered Philip and said, "Please [tell me], of whom does the prophet say this? Of himself, or of someone else?"
44Ac 8:35 And Philip opened his mouth, and beginning from this Scripture he preached Jesus to him.
44Ac 8:36 And as they went along the road they came to some water; and the eunuch *said, "Look! Water! What prevents me from being baptized?"
44Ac 8:37 {And Philip said, "If you believe with all your heart, you may." And he answered and said, "I believe that Jesus Christ is the Son of God."}
44Ac 8:38 And he ordered the chariot to stop; and they both went down into the water, Philip as well as the eunuch; and he baptized him.
44Ac 8:39 And when they came up out of the water, the Spirit of the Lord snatched Philip away; and the eunuch saw him no more, but went on his way rejoicing.
44Ac 8:40 But Philip found himself at Azotus; and as he passed through he kept preaching the gospel to all the cities, until he came to Caesarea.
44Ac 9:1 Now Saul, still breathing threats and murder against the disciples of the Lord, went to the high priest,
44Ac 9:2 and asked for letters from him to the synagogues at Damascus, so that if he found any belonging to the Way, both men and women, he might bring them bound to Jerusalem.
44Ac 9:3 And it came about that as he journeyed, he was approaching Damascus, and suddenly a light from heaven flashed around him;
44Ac 9:4 and he fell to the ground, and heard a voice saying to him, "Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting Me?"
44Ac 9:5 And he said, "Who art Thou, Lord?" And He [said,] "I am Jesus whom you are persecuting,
44Ac 9:6 but rise, and enter the city, and it shall be told you what you must do. "
44Ac 9:7 And the men who traveled with him stood speechless, hearing the voice, but seeing no one.
44Ac 9:8 And Saul got up from the ground, and though his eyes were open, he could see nothing; and leading him by the hand, they brought him into Damascus.
44Ac 9:9 And he was three days without sight, and neither ate nor drank.
44Ac 9:10 Now there was a certain disciple at Damascus, named Ananias; and the Lord said to him in a vision, "Ananias." And he said, "Behold, [here am] I, Lord."
44Ac 9:11 And the Lord [said] to him, "Arise and go to the street called Straight, and inquire at the house of Judas for a man from Tarsus named Saul, for behold, he is praying,
44Ac 9:12 and he has seen in a vision a man named Ananias come in and lay his hands on him, so that he might regain his sight. "
44Ac 9:13 But Ananias answered, "Lord, I have heard from many about this man, how much harm he did to Thy saints at Jerusalem;
44Ac 9:14 and here he has authority from the chief priests to bind all who call upon Thy name. "
44Ac 9:15 But the Lord said to him, "Go, for he is a chosen instrument of Mine, to bear My name before the Gentiles and kings and the sons of Israel;
44Ac 9:16 for I will show him how much he must suffer for My name's sake. "
44Ac 9:17 And Ananias departed and entered the house, and after laying his hands on him said, "Brother Saul, the Lord Jesus, who appeared to you on the road by which you were coming, has sent me so that you may regain your sight, and be filled with the Holy Spirit."
44Ac 9:18 And immediately there fell from his eyes something like scales, and he regained his sight, and he arose and was baptized;
44Ac 9:19 and he took food and was strengthened. Now for several days he was with the disciples who were at Damascus,
44Ac 9:20 and immediately he [began] to proclaim Jesus in the synagogues, saying, "He is the Son of God."
44Ac 9:21 And all those hearing him continued to be amazed, and were saying, " Is this not he who in Jerusalem destroyed those who called on this name, and [who] had come here for the purpose of bringing them bound before the chief priests? "
44Ac 9:22 But Saul kept increasing in strength and confounding the Jews who lived at Damascus by proving that this [Jesus] is the Christ.
44Ac 9:23 And when many days had elapsed, the Jews plotted together to do away with him,
44Ac 9:24 but their plot became known to Saul. And they were also watching the gates day and night so that they might put him to death;
44Ac 9:25 but his disciples took him by night, and let him down through [an opening in] the wall, lowering him in a large basket.
44Ac 9:26 And when he had come to Jerusalem, he was trying to associate with the disciples; and they were all afraid of him, not believing that he was a disciple.
44Ac 9:27 But Barnabas took hold of him and brought him to the apostles and described to them how he had seen the Lord on the road, and that He had talked to him, and how at Damascus he had spoken out boldly in the name of Jesus.
44Ac 9:28 And he was with them moving about freely in Jerusalem, speaking out boldly in the name of the Lord.
44Ac 9:29 And he was talking and arguing with the Hellenistic [Jews;] but they were attempting to put him to death.
44Ac 9:30 But when the brethren learned [of it], they brought him down to Caesarea and sent him away to Tarsus.
44Ac 9:31 So the church throughout all Judea and Galilee and Samaria enjoyed peace, being built up; and, going on in the fear of the Lord and in the comfort of the Holy Spirit, it continued to increase.
44Ac 9:32 Now it came about that as Peter was traveling through all [those parts,] he came down also to the saints who lived at Lydda.
44Ac 9:33 And there he found a certain man named Aeneas, who had been bedridden eight years, for he was paralyzed.
44Ac 9:34 And Peter said to him, "Aeneas, Jesus Christ heals you; arise, and make your bed." And immediately he arose.
44Ac 9:35 And all who lived at Lydda and Sharon saw him, and they turned to the Lord.
44Ac 9:36 Now in Joppa there was a certain disciple named Tabitha (which translated [in Greek] is called Dorcas); this woman was abounding with deeds of kindness and charity, which she continually did.
44Ac 9:37 And it came about at that time that she fell sick and died; and when they had washed her body, they laid it in an upper room.
44Ac 9:38 And since Lydda was near Joppa, the disciples, having heard that Peter was there, sent two men to him, entreating him, "Do not delay to come to us."
44Ac 9:39 And Peter arose and went with them. And when he had come, they brought him into the upper room; and all the widows stood beside him weeping, and showing all the tunics and garments that Dorcas used to make while she was with them.
44Ac 9:40 But Peter sent them all out and knelt down and prayed, and turning to the body, he said, "Tabitha, arise." And she opened her eyes, and when she saw Peter, she sat up.
44Ac 9:41 And he gave her his hand and raised her up; and calling the saints and widows, he presented her alive.
44Ac 9:42 And it became known all over Joppa, and many believed in the Lord.
44Ac 9:43 And it came about that he stayed many days in Joppa with a certain tanner, Simon.
44Ac 10:1 Now [there was] a certain man at Caesarea named Cornelius, a centurion of what was called the Italian cohort,
44Ac 10:2 a devout man, and one who feared God with all his household, and gave many alms to the [Jewish] people, and prayed to God continually.
44Ac 10:3 About the ninth hour of the day he clearly saw in a vision an angel of God who had [just] come in to him, and said to him, "Cornelius!"
44Ac 10:4 And fixing his gaze upon him and being much alarmed, he said, "What is it, Lord?" And he said to him, "Your prayers and alms have ascended as a memorial before God.
44Ac 10:5 "And now dispatch [some] men to Joppa, and send for a man [named] Simon, who is also called Peter;
44Ac 10:6 he is staying with a certain tanner [named] Simon, whose house is by the sea. "
44Ac 10:7 And when the angel who was speaking to him had departed, he summoned two of his servants and a devout soldier of those who were in constant attendance upon him,
44Ac 10:8 and after he had explained everything to them, he sent them to Joppa.
44Ac 10:9 And on the next day, as they were on their way, and approaching the city, Peter went up on the housetop about the sixth hour to pray.
44Ac 10:10 And he became hungry, and was desiring to eat; but while they were making preparations, he fell into a trance;
44Ac 10:11 and he *beheld the sky opened up, and a certain object like a great sheet coming down, lowered by four corners to the ground,
44Ac 10:12 and there were in it all [kinds of] four-footed animals and crawling creatures of the earth and birds of the air.
44Ac 10:13 And a voice came to him, "Arise, Peter, kill and eat!"
44Ac 10:14 But Peter said, "By no means, Lord, for I have never eaten anything unholy and unclean."
44Ac 10:15 And again a voice [came] to him a second time, "What God has cleansed, no [longer] consider unholy."
44Ac 10:16 And this happened three times; and immediately the object was taken up into the sky.
44Ac 10:17 Now while Peter was greatly perplexed in mind as to what the vision which he had seen might be, behold, the men who had been sent by Cornelius, having asked directions for Simon's house, appeared at the gate;
44Ac 10:18 and calling out, they were asking whether Simon, who was also called Peter, was staying there.
44Ac 10:19 And while Peter was reflecting on the vision, the Spirit said to him, "Behold, three men are looking for you.
44Ac 10:20 "But arise, go downstairs, and accompany them without misgivings; for I have sent them Myself."
44Ac 10:21 And Peter went down to the men and said, "Behold, I am the one you are looking for; what is the reason for which you have come?"
44Ac 10:22 And they said, "Cornelius, a centurion, a righteous and God-fearing man well spoken of by the entire nation of the Jews, was [divinely] directed by a holy angel to send for you [to come] to his house and hear a message from you."
44Ac 10:23 And so he invited them in and gave them lodging. And on the next day he arose and went away with them, and some of the brethren from Joppa accompanied him.
44Ac 10:24 And on the following day he entered Caesarea. Now Cornelius was waiting for them, and had called together his relatives and close friends.
44Ac 10:25 And when it came about that Peter entered, Cornelius met him, and fell at his feet and worshiped [him.]
44Ac 10:26 But Peter raised him up, saying, "Stand up; I too am [just] a man."
44Ac 10:27 And as he talked with him, he entered, and found many people assembled.
44Ac 10:28 And he said to them, "You yourselves know how unlawful it is for a man who is a Jew to associate with a foreigner or to visit him; and [yet] God has shown me that I should not call any man unholy or unclean.
44Ac 10:29 "That is why I came without even raising any objection when I was sent for. And so I ask for what reason you have sent for me."
44Ac 10:30 And Cornelius said, "Four days ago to this hour, I was praying in my house during the ninth hour; and behold, a man stood before me in shining garments,
44Ac 10:31 and he *said, 'Cornelius, your prayer has been heard and your alms have been remembered before God.
44Ac 10:32 'Send therefore to Joppa and invite Simon, who is also called Peter, to come to you; he is staying at the house of Simon [the] tanner by the sea.'
44Ac 10:33 "And so I sent to you immediately, and you have been kind enough to come. Now then, we are all here present before God to hear all that you have been commanded by the Lord."
44Ac 10:34 And opening his mouth, Peter said： "I most certainly understand [ now] that God is not one to show partiality,
44Ac 10:35 but in every nation the man who fears Him and does what is right, is welcome to Him.
44Ac 10:36 "The word which He sent to the sons of Israel, preaching peace through Jesus Christ (He is Lord of all)--
44Ac 10:37 you yourselves know the thing which took place throughout all Judea, starting from Galilee, after the baptism which John proclaimed.
44Ac 10:38 "[You know of] Jesus of Nazareth, how God anointed Him with the Holy Spirit and with power, and [how] He went about doing good, and healing all who were oppressed by the devil; for God was with Him.
44Ac 10:39 "And we are witnesses of all the things He did both in the land of the Jews and in Jerusalem. And they also put Him to death by hanging Him on a cross.
44Ac 10:40 "God raised Him up on the third day, and granted that He should become visible,
44Ac 10:41 not to all the people, but to witnesses who were chosen beforehand by God, [that is,] to us, who ate and drank with Him after He arose from the dead.
44Ac 10:42 "And He ordered us to preach to the people, and solemnly to testify that this is the One who has been appointed by God as Judge of the living and the dead.
44Ac 10:43 "Of Him all the prophets bear witness that through His name everyone who believes in Him receives forgiveness of sins."
44Ac 10:44 While Peter was still speaking these words, the Holy Spirit fell upon all those who were listening to the message.
44Ac 10:45 And all the circumcised believers who had come with Peter were amazed, because the gift of the Holy Spirit had been poured out upon the Gentiles also.
44Ac 10:46 For they were hearing them speaking with tongues and exalting God. Then Peter answered,
44Ac 10:47 "Surely no one can refuse the water for these to be baptized who have received the Holy Spirit just as we [did,] can he?"
44Ac 10:48 And he ordered them to be baptized in the name of Jesus Christ. Then they asked him to stay on for a few days.
44Ac 11:1 Now the apostles and the brethren who were throughout Judea heard that the Gentiles also had received the word of God.
44Ac 11:2 And when Peter came up to Jerusalem, those who were circumcised took issue with him,
44Ac 11:3 saying, "You went to uncircumcised men and ate with them."
44Ac 11:4 But Peter began [speaking] and [proceeded] to explain to them in orderly sequence, saying,
44Ac 11:5 "I was in the city of Joppa praying; and in a trance I saw a vision, a certain object coming down like a great sheet lowered by four corners from the sky; and it came right down to me,
44Ac 11:6 and when I had fixed my gaze upon it and was observing it I saw the four-footed animals of the earth and the wild beasts and the crawling creatures and the birds of the air.
44Ac 11:7 "And I also heard a voice saying to me, 'Arise, Peter; kill and eat.'
44Ac 11:8 "But I said, 'By no means, Lord, for nothing unholy or unclean has ever entered my mouth.'
44Ac 11:9 "But a voice from heaven answered a second time, 'What God has cleansed, no longer consider unholy.'
44Ac 11:10 "And this happened three times, and everything was drawn back up into the sky.
44Ac 11:11 "And behold, at that moment three men appeared before the house in which we were [staying,] having been sent to me from Caesarea.
44Ac 11:12 "And the Spirit told me to go with them without misgivings. And these six brethren also went with me, and we entered the man's house.
44Ac 11:13 "And he reported to us how he had seen the angel standing in his house, and saying, 'Send to Joppa, and have Simon, who is also called Peter, brought here;
44Ac 11:14 and he shall speak words to you by which you will be saved, you and all your household. '
44Ac 11:15 "And as I began to speak, the Holy Spirit fell upon them, just as [ He did] upon us at the beginning.
44Ac 11:16 "And I remembered the word of the Lord, how He used to say, 'John baptized with water, but you shall be baptized with the Holy Spirit.'
44Ac 11:17 "If God therefore gave to them the same gift as [He gave] to us also after believing in the Lord Jesus Christ, who was I that I could stand in God's way?"
44Ac 11:18 And when they heard this, they quieted down, and glorified God, saying, "Well then, God has granted to the Gentiles also the repentance [that leads] to life."
44Ac 11:19 So then those who were scattered because of the persecution that arose in connection with Stephen made their way to Phoenicia and Cyprus and Antioch, speaking the word to no one except to Jews alone.
44Ac 11:20 But there were some of them, men of Cyprus and Cyrene, who came to Antioch and [began] speaking to the Greeks also, preaching the Lord Jesus.
44Ac 11:21 And the hand of the Lord was with them, and a large number who believed turned to the Lord.
44Ac 11:22 And the news about them reached the ears of the church at Jerusalem, and they sent Barnabas off to Antioch.
44Ac 11:23 Then when he had come and witnessed the grace of God, he rejoiced and [began] to encourage them all with resolute heart to remain [true] to the Lord;
44Ac 11:24 for he was a good man, and full of the Holy Spirit and of faith. And considerable numbers were brought to the Lord.
44Ac 11:25 And he left for Tarsus to look for Saul;
44Ac 11:26 and when he had found him, he brought him to Antioch. And it came about that for an entire year they met with the church, and taught considerable numbers; and the disciples were first called Christians in Antioch.
44Ac 11:27 Now at this time some prophets came down from Jerusalem to Antioch.
44Ac 11:28 And one of them named Agabus stood up and [began] to indicate by the Spirit that there would certainly be a great famine all over the world. And this took place in the [reign] of Claudius.
44Ac 11:29 And in the proportion that any of the disciples had means, each of them determined to send [a contribution] for the relief of the brethren living in Judea.
44Ac 11:30 And this they did, sending it in charge of Barnabas and Saul to the elders.
44Ac 12:1 Now about that time Herod the king laid hands on some who belonged to the church, in order to mistreat them.
44Ac 12:2 And he had James the brother of John put to death with a sword.
44Ac 12:3 And when he saw that it pleased the Jews, he proceeded to arrest Peter also. Now it was during the days of Unleavened Bread.
44Ac 12:4 And when he had seized him, he put him in prison, delivering him to four squads of soldiers to guard him, intending after the Passover to bring him out before the people.
44Ac 12:5 So Peter was kept in the prison, but prayer for him was being made fervently by the church to God.
44Ac 12:6 And on the very night when Herod was about to bring him forward, Peter was sleeping between two soldiers, bound with two chains; and guards in front of the door were watching over the prison.
44Ac 12:7 And behold, an angel of the Lord suddenly appeared, and a light shone in the cell; and he struck Peter's side and roused him, saying, "Get up quickly." And his chains fell off his hands.
44Ac 12:8 And the angel said to him, "Gird yourself and put on your sandals." And he did so. And he *said to him," Wrap your cloak around you and follow me. "
44Ac 12:9 And he went out and continued to follow, and he did not know that what was being done by the angel was real, but thought he was seeing a vision.
44Ac 12:10 And when they had passed the first and second guard, they came to the iron gate that leads into the city, which opened for them by itself; and they went out and went along one street; and immediately the angel departed from him.
44Ac 12:11 And when Peter came to himself, he said, "Now I know for sure that the Lord has sent forth His angel and rescued me from the hand of Herod and from all that the Jewish people were expecting."
44Ac 12:12 And when he realized [this,] he went to the house of Mary, the mother of John who was also called Mark, where many were gathered together and were praying.
44Ac 12:13 And when he knocked at the door of the gate, a servant-girl named Rhoda came to answer.
44Ac 12:14 And when she recognized Peter's voice, because of her joy she did not open the gate, but ran in and announced that Peter was standing in front of the gate.
44Ac 12:15 And they said to her, "You are out of your mind!" But she kept insisting that it was so. And they kept saying, "It is his angel."
44Ac 12:16 But Peter continued knocking; and when they had opened [the door], they saw him and were amazed.
44Ac 12:17 But motioning to them with his hand to be silent, he described to them how the Lord had led him out of the prison. And he said, "Report these things to James and the brethren." And he departed and went to another place.
44Ac 12:18 Now when day came, there was no small disturbance among the soldiers [as to] what could have become of Peter.
44Ac 12:19 And when Herod had searched for him and had not found him, he examined the guards and ordered that they be led away [to execution.] And he went down from Judea to Caesarea and was spending time there.
44Ac 12:20 Now he was very angry with the people of Tyre and Sidon; and with one accord they came to him, and having won over Blastus the king's chamberlain, they were asking for peace, because their country was fed by the king's country.
44Ac 12:21 And on an appointed day Herod, having put on his royal apparel, took his seat on the rostrum and [began] delivering an address to them.
44Ac 12:22 And the people kept crying out, "The voice of a god and not of a man!"
44Ac 12:23 And immediately an angel of the Lord struck him because he did not give God the glory, and he was eaten by worms and died.
44Ac 12:24 But the word of the Lord continued to grow and to be multiplied.
44Ac 12:25 And Barnabas and Saul returned from Jerusalem when they had fulfilled their mission, taking along with [them] John, who was also called Mark.
44Ac 13:1 Now there were at Antioch, in the church that was [there], prophets and teachers： Barnabas, and Simeon who was called Niger, and Lucius of Cyrene, and Manaen who had been brought up with Herod the tetrarch, and Saul.
44Ac 13:2 And while they were ministering to the Lord and fasting, the Holy Spirit said, "Set apart for Me Barnabas and Saul for the work to which I have called them."
44Ac 13:3 Then, when they had fasted and prayed and laid their hands on them, they sent them away.
44Ac 13:4 So, being sent out by the Holy Spirit, they went down to Seleucia and from there they sailed to Cyprus.
44Ac 13:5 And when they reached Salamis, they [began] to proclaim the word of God in the synagogues of the Jews; and they also had John as their helper.
44Ac 13:6 And when they had gone through the whole island as far as Paphos, they found a certain magician, a Jewish false prophet whose name was Bar-jesus,
44Ac 13:7 who was with the proconsul, Sergius Paulus, a man of intelligence. This man summoned Barnabas and Saul and sought to hear the word of God.
44Ac 13:8 But Elymas the magician (for thus his name is translated) was opposing them, seeking to turn the proconsul away from the faith.
44Ac 13:9 But Saul, who was also [known as] Paul, filled with the Holy Spirit, fixed his gaze upon him,
44Ac 13:10 and said, "You who are full of all deceit and fraud, you son of the devil, you enemy of all righteousness, will you not cease to make crooked the straight ways of the Lord?
44Ac 13:11 "And now, behold, the hand of the Lord is upon you, and you will be blind and not see the sun for a time." And immediately a mist and a darkness fell upon him, and he went about seeking those who would lead him by the hand.
44Ac 13:12 Then the proconsul believed when he saw what had happened, being amazed at the teaching of the Lord.
44Ac 13:13 Now Paul and his companions put out to sea from Paphos and came to Perga in Pamphylia; and John left them and returned to Jerusalem.
44Ac 13:14 But going on from Perga, they arrived at Pisidian Antioch, and on the Sabbath day they went into the synagogue and sat down.
44Ac 13:15 And after the reading of the Law and the Prophets the synagogue officials sent to them, saying, "Brethren, if you have any word of exhortation for the people, say it."
44Ac 13:16 And Paul stood up, and motioning with his hand, he said, "Men of Israel, and you who fear God, listen：
44Ac 13:17 "The God of this people Israel chose our fathers, and made the people great during their stay in the land of Egypt, and with an uplifted arm He led them out from it.
44Ac 13:18 "And for a period of about forty years He put up with them in the wilderness.
44Ac 13:19 "And when He had destroyed seven nations in the land of Canaan, He distributed their land as an inheritance-- [all of which took] about four hundred and fifty years.
44Ac 13:20 "And after these things He gave [them] judges until Samuel the prophet.
44Ac 13:21 "And then they asked for a king, and God gave them Saul the son of Kish, a man of the tribe of Benjamin, for forty years.
44Ac 13:22 "And after He had removed him, He raised up David to be their king, concerning whom He also testified and said, 'I HAVE FOUND DAVID the son of Jesse, A MAN AFTER MY HEART, who will do all My will.'
44Ac 13:23 "From the offspring of this man, according to promise, God has brought to Israel a Savior, Jesus,
44Ac 13:24 after John had proclaimed before His coming a baptism of repentance to all the people of Israel.
44Ac 13:25 "And while John was completing his course, he kept saying, 'What do you suppose that I am? I am not [He.] But behold, one is coming after me the sandals of whose feet I am not worthy to untie.'
44Ac 13:26 "Brethren, sons of Abraham's family, and those among you who fear God, to us the word of this salvation is sent out.
44Ac 13:27 "For those who live in Jerusalem, and their rulers, recognizing neither Him nor the utterances of the prophets which are read every Sabbath, fulfilled [these] by condemning [Him].
44Ac 13:28 "And though they found no ground for [putting Him to] death, they asked Pilate that He be executed.
44Ac 13:29 "And when they had carried out all that was written concerning Him, they took Him down from the cross and laid Him in a tomb.
44Ac 13:30 "But God raised Him from the dead;
44Ac 13:31 and for many days He appeared to those who came up with Him from Galilee to Jerusalem, the very ones who are now His witnesses to the people.
44Ac 13:32 "And we preach to you the good news of the promise made to the fathers,
44Ac 13:33 that God has fulfilled this [promise] to our children in that He raised up Jesus, as it is also written in the second Psalm, 'THOU ART MY SON; TODAY I HAVE BEGOTTEN THEE.'
44Ac 13:34 "[And as for the fact] that He raised Him up from the dead, no more to return to decay, He has spoken in this way： 'I WILL GIVE YOU THE HOLY [and] SURE [blessings] OF DAVID.'
44Ac 13:35 "Therefore He also says in another [Psalm,] 'THOU WILT NOT ALLOW THY HOLY ONE TO UNDERGO DECAY.'
44Ac 13:36 "For David, after he had served the purpose of God in his own generation, fell asleep, and was laid among his fathers, and underwent decay;
44Ac 13:37 but He whom God raised did not undergo decay.
44Ac 13:38 "Therefore let it be known to you, brethren, that through Him forgiveness of sins is proclaimed to you,
44Ac 13:39 and through Him everyone who believes is freed from all things, from which you could not be freed through the Law of Moses.
44Ac 13:40 "Take heed therefore, so that the thing spoken of in the Prophets may not come upon [you]：
44Ac 13:41 'BEHOLD, YOU SCOFFERS, AND MARVEL, AND PERISH; FOR I AM ACCOMPLISHING A WORK IN YOUR DAYS, A WORK WHICH YOU WILL NEVER BELIEVE, THOUGH SOMEONE SHOULD DESCRIBE IT TO YOU.' "
44Ac 13:42 And as Paul and Barnabas were going out, the people kept begging that these things might be spoken to them the next Sabbath.
44Ac 13:43 Now when [the meeting of] the synagogue had broken up, many of the Jews and of the God-fearing proselytes followed Paul and Barnabas, who, speaking to them, were urging them to continue in the grace of God.
44Ac 13:44 And the next Sabbath nearly the whole city assembled to hear the word of God.
44Ac 13:45 But when the Jews saw the crowds, they were filled with jealousy, and [began] contradicting the things spoken by Paul, and were blaspheming.
44Ac 13:46 And Paul and Barnabas spoke out boldly and said, "It was necessary that the word of God should be spoken to you first; since you repudiate it, and judge yourselves unworthy of eternal life, behold, we are turning to the Gentiles.
44Ac 13:47 "For thus the Lord has commanded us, 'I HAVE PLACED YOU AS A LIGHT FOR THE GENTILES, THAT YOU SHOULD BRING SALVATION TO THE END OF THE EARTH.'"
44Ac 13:48 And when the Gentiles heard this, they [began] rejoicing and glorifying the word of the Lord; and as many as had been appointed to eternal life believed.
44Ac 13:49 And the word of the Lord was being spread through the whole region.
44Ac 13:50 But the Jews aroused the devout women of prominence and the leading men of the city, and instigated a persecution against Paul and Barnabas, and drove them out of their district.
44Ac 13:51 But they shook off the dust of their feet [in protest] against them and went to Iconium.
44Ac 13:52 And the disciples were continually filled with joy and with the Holy Spirit.
44Ac 14:1 And it came about that in Iconium they entered the synagogue of the Jews together, and spoke in such a manner that a great multitude believed, both of Jews and of Greeks.
44Ac 14:2 But the Jews who disbelieved stirred up the minds of the Gentiles, and embittered them against the brethren.
44Ac 14:3 Therefore they spent a long time [there] speaking boldly [with reliance] upon the Lord, who was bearing witness to the word of His grace, granting that signs and wonders be done by their hands.
44Ac 14:4 But the multitude of the city was divided; and some sided with the Jews, and some with the apostles.
44Ac 14:5 And when an attempt was made by both the Gentiles and the Jews with their rulers, to mistreat and to stone them,
44Ac 14:6 they became aware of it and fled to the cities of Lycaonia, Lystra and Derbe, and the surrounding region;
44Ac 14:7 and there they continued to preach the gospel.
44Ac 14:8 And at Lystra there was sitting a certain man, without strength in his feet, lame from his mother's womb, who had never walked.
44Ac 14:9 This man was listening to Paul as he spoke, who, when he had fixed his gaze upon him, and had seen that he had faith to be made well,
44Ac 14:10 said with a loud voice, "Stand upright on your feet." And he leaped up and [began] to walk.
44Ac 14:11 And when the multitudes saw what Paul had done, they raised their voice, saying in the Lycaonian language, "The gods have become like men and have come down to us."
44Ac 14:12 And they [began] calling Barnabas, Zeus, and Paul, Hermes, because he was the chief speaker.
44Ac 14:13 And the priest of Zeus, whose [temple] was just outside the city, brought oxen and garlands to the gates, and wanted to offer sacrifice with the crowds.
44Ac 14:14 But when the apostles, Barnabas and Paul, heard of it, they tore their robes and rushed out into the crowd, crying out
44Ac 14:15 and saying, "Men, why are you doing these things? We are also men of the same nature as you, and preach the gospel to you in order that you should turn from these vain things to a living God, WHO MADE THE HEAVEN AND THE EARTH AND THE SEA, AND ALL THAT IS IN THEM.
44Ac 14:16 "And in the generations gone by He permitted all the nations to go their own ways;
44Ac 14:17 and yet He did not leave Himself without witness, in that He did good and gave you rains from heaven and fruitful seasons, satisfying your hearts with food and gladness. "
44Ac 14:18 And [even] saying these things, they with difficulty restrained the crowds from offering sacrifice to them.
44Ac 14:19 But Jews came from Antioch and Iconium, and having won over the multitudes, they stoned Paul and dragged him out of the city, supposing him to be dead.
44Ac 14:20 But while the disciples stood around him, he arose and entered the city. And the next day he went away with Barnabas to Derbe.
44Ac 14:21 And after they had preached the gospel to that city and had made many disciples, they returned to Lystra and to Iconium and to Antioch,
44Ac 14:22 strengthening the souls of the disciples, encouraging them to continue in the faith, and [saying,] "Through many tribulations we must enter the kingdom of God."
44Ac 14:23 And when they had appointed elders for them in every church, having prayed with fasting, they commended them to the Lord in whom they had believed.
44Ac 14:24 And they passed through Pisidia and came into Pamphylia.
44Ac 14:25 And when they had spoken the word in Perga, they went down to Attalia;
44Ac 14:26 and from there they sailed to Antioch, from which they had been commended to the grace of God for the work that they had accomplished.
44Ac 14:27 And when they had arrived and gathered the church together, they [ began] to report all things that God had done with them and how He had opened a door of faith to the Gentiles.
44Ac 14:28 And they spent a long time with the disciples.
44Ac 15:1 And some men came down from Judea and [began] teaching the brethren, "Unless you are circumcised according to the custom of Moses, you cannot be saved."
44Ac 15:2 And when Paul and Barnabas had great dissension and debate with them, [the brethren] determined that Paul and Barnabas and certain others of them should go up to Jerusalem to the apostles and elders concerning this issue.
44Ac 15:3 Therefore, being sent on their way by the church, they were passing through both Phoenicia and Samaria, describing in detail the conversion of the Gentiles, and were bringing great joy to all the brethren.
44Ac 15:4 And when they arrived at Jerusalem, they were received by the church and the apostles and the elders, and they reported all that God had done with them.
44Ac 15:5 But certain ones of the sect of the Pharisees who had believed, stood up, saying, "It is necessary to circumcise them, and to direct them to observe the Law of Moses."
44Ac 15:6 And the apostles and the elders came together to look into this matter.
44Ac 15:7 And after there had been much debate, Peter stood up and said to them, "Brethren, you know that in the early days God made a choice among you, that by my mouth the Gentiles should hear the word of the gospel and believe.
44Ac 15:8 "And God, who knows the heart, bore witness to them, giving them the Holy Spirit, just as He also did to us;
44Ac 15:9 and He made no distinction between us and them, cleansing their hearts by faith.
44Ac 15:10 "Now therefore why do you put God to the test by placing upon the neck of the disciples a yoke which neither our fathers nor we have been able to bear?
44Ac 15:11 "But we believe that we are saved through the grace of the Lord Jesus, in the same way as they also are."
44Ac 15:12 And all the multitude kept silent, and they were listening to Barnabas and Paul as they were relating what signs and wonders God had done through them among the Gentiles.
44Ac 15:13 And after they had stopped speaking, James answered, saying, "Brethren, listen to me.
44Ac 15:14 "Simeon has related how God first concerned Himself about taking from among the Gentiles a people for His name.
44Ac 15:15 "And with this the words of the Prophets agree, just as it is written,
44Ac 15:16 'AFTER THESE THINGS I will return, AND I WILL REBUILD THE TABERNACLE OF DAVID WHICH HAS FALLEN, AND I WILL REBUILD ITS RUINS, AND I WILL RESTORE IT,
44Ac 15:17 IN ORDER THAT THE REST OF MANKIND MAY SEEK THE LORD, AND ALL THE GENTILES WHO ARE CALLED BY MY NAME, '
44Ac 15:18 SAYS THE LORD, WHO MAKES THESE THINGS KNOWN FROM OF OLD.
44Ac 15:19 "Therefore it is my judgment that we do not trouble those who are turning to God from among the Gentiles,
44Ac 15:20 but that we write to them that they abstain from things contaminated by idols and from fornication and from what is strangled and from blood.
44Ac 15:21 "For Moses from ancient generations has in every city those who preach him, since he is read in the synagogues every Sabbath."
44Ac 15:22 Then it seemed good to the apostles and the elders, with the whole church, to choose men from among them to send to Antioch with Paul and Barnabas-- Judas called Barsabbas, and Silas, leading men among the brethren,
44Ac 15:23 and they sent this letter by them, "The apostles and the brethren who are elders, to the brethren in Antioch and Syria and Cilicia who are from the Gentiles, greetings.
44Ac 15:24 "Since we have heard that some of our number to whom we gave no instruction have disturbed you with [their] words, unsettling your souls,
44Ac 15:25 it seemed good to us, having become of one mind, to select men to send to you with our beloved Barnabas and Paul,
44Ac 15:26 men who have risked their lives for the name of our Lord Jesus Christ.
44Ac 15:27 "Therefore we have sent Judas and Silas, who themselves will also report the same things by word [of mouth].
44Ac 15:28 "For it seemed good to the Holy Spirit and to us to lay upon you no greater burden than these essentials：
44Ac 15:29 that you abstain from things sacrificed to idols and from blood and from things strangled and from fornication; if you keep yourselves free from such things, you will do well. Farewell. "
44Ac 15:30 So, when they were sent away, they went down to Antioch; and having gathered the congregation together, they delivered the letter.
44Ac 15:31 And when they had read it, they rejoiced because of its encouragement.
44Ac 15:32 And Judas and Silas, also being prophets themselves, encouraged and strengthened the brethren with a lengthy message.
44Ac 15:33 And after they had spent time [there], they were sent away from the brethren in peace to those who had sent them out.
44Ac 15:34 {But it seemed good to Silas to remain there.}
44Ac 15:35 But Paul and Barnabas stayed in Antioch, teaching and preaching, with many others also, the word of the Lord.
44Ac 15:36 And after some days Paul said to Barnabas, "Let us return and visit the brethren in every city in which we proclaimed the word of the Lord, [and see] how they are."
44Ac 15:37 And Barnabas was desirous of taking John, called Mark, along with them also.
44Ac 15:38 But Paul kept insisting that they should not take him along who had deserted them in Pamphylia and had not gone with them to the work.
44Ac 15:39 And there arose such a sharp disagreement that they separated from one another, and Barnabas took Mark with him and sailed away to Cyprus.
44Ac 15:40 But Paul chose Silas and departed, being committed by the brethren to the grace of the Lord.
44Ac 15:41 And he was traveling through Syria and Cilicia, strengthening the churches.
44Ac 16:1 And he came also to Derbe and to Lystra. And behold, a certain disciple was there, named Timothy, the son of a Jewish woman who was a believer, but his father was a Greek,
44Ac 16:2 and he was well spoken of by the brethren who were in Lystra and Iconium.
44Ac 16:3 Paul wanted this man to go with him; and he took him and circumcised him because of the Jews who were in those parts, for they all knew that his father was a Greek.
44Ac 16:4 Now while they were passing through the cities, they were delivering the decrees, which had been decided upon by the apostles and elders who were in Jerusalem, for them to observe.
44Ac 16:5 So the churches were being strengthened in the faith, and were increasing in number daily.
44Ac 16:6 And they passed through the Phrygian and Galatian region, having been forbidden by the Holy Spirit to speak the word in Asia;
44Ac 16:7 and when they had come to Mysia, they were trying to go into Bithynia, and the Spirit of Jesus did not permit them;
44Ac 16:8 and passing by Mysia, they came down to Troas.
44Ac 16:9 And a vision appeared to Paul in the night： a certain man of Macedonia was standing and appealing to him, and saying, "Come over to Macedonia and help us."
44Ac 16:10 And when he had seen the vision, immediately we sought to go into Macedonia, concluding that God had called us to preach the gospel to them.
44Ac 16:11 Therefore putting out to sea from Troas, we ran a straight course to Samothrace, and on the day following to Neapolis;
44Ac 16:12 and from there to Philippi, which is a leading city of the district of Macedonia, a [Roman] colony; and we were staying in this city for some days.
44Ac 16:13 And on the Sabbath day we went outside the gate to a riverside, where we were supposing that there would be a place of prayer; and we sat down and began speaking to the women who had assembled.
44Ac 16:14 And a certain woman named Lydia, from the city of Thyatira, a seller of purple fabrics, a worshiper of God, was listening; and the Lord opened her heart to respond to the things spoken by Paul.
44Ac 16:15 And when she and her household had been baptized, she urged us, saying, "If you have judged me to be faithful to the Lord, come into my house and stay." And she prevailed upon us.
44Ac 16:16 And it happened that as we were going to the place of prayer, a certain slave-girl having a spirit of divination met us, who was bringing her masters much profit by fortunetelling.
44Ac 16:17 Following after Paul and us, she kept crying out, saying, "These men are bond-servants of the Most High God, who are proclaiming to you the way of salvation."
44Ac 16:18 And she continued doing this for many days. But Paul was greatly annoyed, and turned and said to the spirit, "I command you in the name of Jesus Christ to come out of her!" And it came out at that very moment.
44Ac 16:19 But when her masters saw that their hope of profit was gone, they seized Paul and Silas and dragged them into the market place before the authorities,
44Ac 16:20 and when they had brought them to the chief magistrates, they said, "These men are throwing our city into confusion, being Jews,
44Ac 16:21 and are proclaiming customs which it is not lawful for us to accept or to observe, being Romans. "
44Ac 16:22 And the crowd rose up together against them, and the chief magistrates tore their robes off them, and proceeded to order [them] to be beaten with rods.
44Ac 16:23 And when they had inflicted many blows upon them, they threw them into prison, commanding the jailer to guard them securely;
44Ac 16:24 and he, having received such a command, threw them into the inner prison, and fastened their feet in the stocks.
44Ac 16:25 But about midnight Paul and Silas were praying and singing hymns of praise to God, and the prisoners were listening to them;
44Ac 16:26 and suddenly there came a great earthquake, so that the foundations of the prison house were shaken; and immediately all the doors were opened, and everyone's chains were unfastened.
44Ac 16:27 And when the jailer had been roused out of sleep and had seen the prison doors opened, he drew his sword and was about to kill himself, supposing that the prisoners had escaped.
44Ac 16:28 But Paul cried out with a loud voice, saying, "Do yourself no harm, for we are all here!"
44Ac 16:29 And he called for lights and rushed in and, trembling with fear, he fell down before Paul and Silas,
44Ac 16:30 and after he brought them out, he said, "Sirs, what must I do to be saved?"
44Ac 16:31 And they said, "Believe in the Lord Jesus, and you shall be saved, you and your household."
44Ac 16:32 And they spoke the word of the Lord to him together with all who were in his house.
44Ac 16:33 And he took them that [very] hour of the night and washed their wounds, and immediately he was baptized, he and all his [household.]
44Ac 16:34 And he brought them into his house and set food before them, and rejoiced greatly, having believed in God with his whole household.
44Ac 16:35 Now when day came, the chief magistrates sent their policemen, saying, "Release those men."
44Ac 16:36 And the jailer reported these words to Paul, [saying,] "The chief magistrates have sent to release you. Now therefore, come out and go in peace."
44Ac 16:37 But Paul said to them, "They have beaten us in public without trial, men who are Romans, and have thrown us into prison; and now are they sending us away secretly? No indeed! But let them come themselves and bring us out."
44Ac 16:38 And the policemen reported these words to the chief magistrates. And they were afraid when they heard that they were Romans,
44Ac 16:39 and they came and appealed to them, and when they had brought them out, they kept begging them to leave the city.
44Ac 16:40 And they went out of the prison and entered [the house of] Lydia, and when they saw the brethren, they encouraged them and departed.
44Ac 17:1 Now when they had traveled through Amphipolis and Apollonia, they came to Thessalonica, where there was a synagogue of the Jews.
44Ac 17:2 And according to Paul's custom, he went to them, and for three Sabbaths reasoned with them from the Scriptures,
44Ac 17:3 explaining and giving evidence that the Christ had to suffer and rise again from the dead, and [saying,] "This Jesus whom I am proclaiming to you is the Christ."
44Ac 17:4 And some of them were persuaded and joined Paul and Silas, along with a great multitude of the God-fearing Greeks and a number of the leading women.
44Ac 17:5 But the Jews, becoming jealous and taking along some wicked men from the market place, formed a mob and set the city in an uproar; and coming upon the house of Jason, they were seeking to bring them out to the people.
44Ac 17:6 And when they did not find them, they [began] dragging Jason and some brethren before the city authorities, shouting, "These men who have upset the world have come here also;
44Ac 17:7 and Jason has welcomed them, and they all act contrary to the decrees of Caesar, saying that there is another king, Jesus. "
44Ac 17:8 And they stirred up the crowd and the city authorities who heard these things.
44Ac 17:9 And when they had received a pledge from Jason and the others, they released them.
44Ac 17:10 And the brethren immediately sent Paul and Silas away by night to Berea; and when they arrived, they went into the synagogue of the Jews.
44Ac 17:11 Now these were more noble-minded than those in Thessalonica, for they received the word with great eagerness, examining the Scriptures daily, [ to see] whether these things were so.
44Ac 17:12 Many of them therefore believed, along with a number of prominent Greek women and men.
44Ac 17:13 But when the Jews of Thessalonica found out that the word of God had been proclaimed by Paul in Berea also, they came there likewise, agitating and stirring up the crowds.
44Ac 17:14 And then immediately the brethren sent Paul out to go as far as the sea; and Silas and Timothy remained there.
44Ac 17:15 Now those who conducted Paul brought him as far as Athens; and receiving a command for Silas and Timothy to come to him as soon as possible, they departed.
44Ac 17:16 Now while Paul was waiting for them at Athens, his spirit was being provoked within him as he was beholding the city full of idols.
44Ac 17:17 So he was reasoning in the synagogue with the Jews and the God-fearing [Gentiles,] and in the market place every day with those who happened to be present.
44Ac 17:18 And also some of the Epicurean and Stoic philosophers were conversing with him. And some were saying, "What would this idle babbler wish to say?" Others, "He seems to be a proclaimer of strange deities,"-- because he was preaching Jesus and the resurrection.
44Ac 17:19 And they took him and brought him to the Areopagus, saying, "May we know what this new teaching is which you are proclaiming?
44Ac 17:20 "For you are bringing some strange things to our ears; we want to know therefore what these things mean."
44Ac 17:21 (Now all the Athenians and the strangers visiting there used to spend their time in nothing other than telling or hearing something new.)
44Ac 17:22 And Paul stood in the midst of the Areopagus and said, "Men of Athens, I observe that you are very religious in all respects.
44Ac 17:23 "For while I was passing through and examining the objects of your worship, I also found an altar with this inscription, 'TO AN UNKNOWN GOD.' What therefore you worship in ignorance, this I proclaim to you.
44Ac 17:24 "The God who made the world and all things in it, since He is Lord of heaven and earth, does not dwell in temples made with hands;
44Ac 17:25 neither is He served by human hands, as though He needed anything, since He Himself gives to all life and breath and all things;
44Ac 17:26 and He made from one, every nation of mankind to live on all the face of the earth, having determined [their] appointed times, and the boundaries of their habitation,
44Ac 17:27 that they should seek God, if perhaps they might grope for Him and find Him, though He is not far from each one of us;
44Ac 17:28 for in Him we live and move and exist, as even some of your own poets have said, 'For we also are His offspring.'
44Ac 17:29 "Being then the offspring of God, we ought not to think that the Divine Nature is like gold or silver or stone, an image formed by the art and thought of man.
44Ac 17:30 "Therefore having overlooked the times of ignorance, God is now declaring to men that all everywhere should repent,
44Ac 17:31 because He has fixed a day in which He will judge the world in righteousness through a Man whom He has appointed, having furnished proof to all men by raising Him from the dead. "
44Ac 17:32 Now when they heard of the resurrection of the dead, some [began] to sneer, but others said, "We shall hear you again concerning this."
44Ac 17:33 So Paul went out of their midst.
44Ac 17:34 But some men joined him and believed, among whom also were Dionysius the Areopagite and a woman named Damaris and others with them.
44Ac 18:1 After these things he left Athens and went to Corinth.
44Ac 18:2 And he found a certain Jew named Aquila, a native of Pontus, having recently come from Italy with his wife Priscilla, because Claudius had commanded all the Jews to leave Rome. He came to them,
44Ac 18:3 and because he was of the same trade, he stayed with them and they were working; for by trade they were tent-makers.
44Ac 18:4 And he was reasoning in the synagogue every Sabbath and trying to persuade Jews and Greeks.
44Ac 18:5 But when Silas and Timothy came down from Macedonia, Paul [began] devoting himself completely to the word, solemnly testifying to the Jews that Jesus was the Christ.
44Ac 18:6 And when they resisted and blasphemed, he shook out his garments and said to them, "Your blood [be] upon your own heads! I am clean. From now on I shall go to the Gentiles."
44Ac 18:7 And he departed from there and went to the house of a certain man named Titius Justus, a worshiper of God, whose house was next to the synagogue.
44Ac 18:8 And Crispus, the leader of the synagogue, believed in the Lord with all his household, and many of the Corinthians when they heard were believing and being baptized.
44Ac 18:9 And the Lord said to Paul in the night by a vision, "Do not be afraid [any longer], but go on speaking and do not be silent;
44Ac 18:10 for I am with you, and no man will attack you in order to harm you, for I have many people in this city. "
44Ac 18:11 And he settled [there] a year and six months, teaching the word of God among them.
44Ac 18:12 But while Gallio was proconsul of Achaia, the Jews with one accord rose up against Paul and brought him before the judgment seat,
44Ac 18:13 saying, "This man persuades men to worship God contrary to the law."
44Ac 18:14 But when Paul was about to open his mouth, Gallio said to the Jews, "If it were a matter of wrong or of vicious crime, O Jews, it would be reasonable for me to put up with you;
44Ac 18:15 but if there are questions about words and names and your own law, look after it yourselves; I am unwilling to be a judge of these matters. "
44Ac 18:16 And he drove them away from the judgment seat.
44Ac 18:17 And they all took hold of Sosthenes, the leader of the synagogue, and [began] beating him in front of the judgment seat. And Gallio was not concerned about any of these things.
44Ac 18:18 And Paul, having remained many days longer, took leave of the brethren and put out to sea for Syria, and with him were Priscilla and Aquila. In Cenchrea he had his hair cut, for he was keeping a vow.
44Ac 18:19 And they came to Ephesus, and he left them there. Now he himself entered the synagogue and reasoned with the Jews.
44Ac 18:20 And when they asked him to stay for a longer time, he did not consent,
44Ac 18:21 but taking leave of them and saying, "I will return to you again if God wills," he set sail from Ephesus.
44Ac 18:22 And when he had landed at Caesarea, he went up and greeted the church, and went down to Antioch.
44Ac 18:23 And having spent some time [there,] he departed and passed successively through the Galatian region and Phrygia, strengthening all the disciples.
44Ac 18:24 Now a certain Jew named Apollos, an Alexandrian by birth, an eloquent man, came to Ephesus; and he was mighty in the Scriptures.
44Ac 18:25 This man had been instructed in the way of the Lord; and being fervent in spirit, he was speaking and teaching accurately the things concerning Jesus, being acquainted only with the baptism of John;
44Ac 18:26 and he began to speak out boldly in the synagogue. But when Priscilla and Aquila heard him, they took him aside and explained to him the way of God more accurately.
44Ac 18:27 And when he wanted to go across to Achaia, the brethren encouraged him and wrote to the disciples to welcome him; and when he had arrived, he helped greatly those who had believed through grace;
44Ac 18:28 for he powerfully refuted the Jews in public, demonstrating by the Scriptures that Jesus was the Christ.
44Ac 19:1 And it came about that while Apollos was at Corinth, Paul having passed through the upper country came to Ephesus, and found some disciples,
44Ac 19:2 and he said to them, "Did you receive the Holy Spirit when you believed?" And they [said] to him, "No, we have not even heard whether there is a Holy Spirit."
44Ac 19:3 And he said, "Into what then were you baptized?" And they said, "Into John's baptism."
44Ac 19:4 And Paul said, "John baptized with the baptism of repentance, telling the people to believe in Him who was coming after him, that is, in Jesus."
44Ac 19:5 And when they heard this, they were baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus.
44Ac 19:6 And when Paul had laid his hands upon them, the Holy Spirit came on them, and they [began] speaking with tongues and prophesying.
44Ac 19:7 And there were in all about twelve men.
44Ac 19:8 And he entered the synagogue and continued speaking out boldly for three months, reasoning and persuading [them] about the kingdom of God.
44Ac 19:9 But when some were becoming hardened and disobedient, speaking evil of the Way before the multitude, he withdrew from them and took away the disciples, reasoning daily in the school of Tyrannus.
44Ac 19:10 And this took place for two years, so that all who lived in Asia heard the word of the Lord, both Jews and Greeks.
44Ac 19:11 And God was performing extraordinary miracles by the hands of Paul,
44Ac 19:12 so that handkerchiefs or aprons were even carried from his body to the sick, and the diseases left them and the evil spirits went out.
44Ac 19:13 But also some of the Jewish exorcists, who went from place to place, attempted to name over those who had the evil spirits the name of the Lord Jesus, saying, "I adjure you by Jesus whom Paul preaches."
44Ac 19:14 And seven sons of one Sceva, a Jewish chief priest, were doing this.
44Ac 19:15 And the evil spirit answered and said to them, "I recognize Jesus, and I know about Paul, but who are you?"
44Ac 19:16 And the man, in whom was the evil spirit, leaped on them and subdued all of them and overpowered them, so that they fled out of that house naked and wounded.
44Ac 19:17 And this became known to all, both Jews and Greeks, who lived in Ephesus; and fear fell upon them all and the name of the Lord Jesus was being magnified.
44Ac 19:18 Many also of those who had believed kept coming, confessing and disclosing their practices.
44Ac 19:19 And many of those who practiced magic brought their books together and [began] burning them in the sight of all; and they counted up the price of them and found it fifty thousand pieces of silver.
44Ac 19:20 So the word of the Lord was growing mightily and prevailing.
44Ac 19:21 Now after these things were finished, Paul purposed in the spirit to go to Jerusalem after he had passed through Macedonia and Achaia, saying, "After I have been there, I must also see Rome."
44Ac 19:22 And having sent into Macedonia two of those who ministered to him, Timothy and Erastus, he himself stayed in Asia for a while.
44Ac 19:23 And about that time there arose no small disturbance concerning the Way.
44Ac 19:24 For a certain man named Demetrius, a silversmith, who made silver shrines of Artemis, was bringing no little business to the craftsmen;
44Ac 19:25 these he gathered together with the workmen of similar [trades,] and said, "Men, you know that our prosperity depends upon this business.
44Ac 19:26 "And you see and hear that not only in Ephesus, but in almost all of Asia, this Paul has persuaded and turned away a considerable number of people, saying that gods made with hands are no gods [at all.]
44Ac 19:27 "And not only is there danger that this trade of ours fall into disrepute, but also that the temple of the great goddess Artemis be regarded as worthless and that she whom all of Asia and the world worship should even be dethroned from her magnificence."
44Ac 19:28 And when they heard [this] and were filled with rage, they [began] crying out, saying, "Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!"
44Ac 19:29 And the city was filled with the confusion, and they rushed with one accord into the theater, dragging along Gaius and Aristarchus, Paul's traveling companions from Macedonia.
44Ac 19:30 And when Paul wanted to go into the assembly, the disciples would not let him.
44Ac 19:31 And also some of the Asiarchs who were friends of his sent to him and repeatedly urged him not to venture into the theater.
44Ac 19:32 So then, some were shouting one thing and some another, for the assembly was in confusion, and the majority did not know for what cause they had come together.
44Ac 19:33 And some of the crowd concluded [it was] Alexander, since the Jews had put him forward; and having motioned with his hand, Alexander was intending to make a defense to the assembly.
44Ac 19:34 But when they recognized that he was a Jew, a [single] outcry arose from them all as they shouted for about two hours, "Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!"
44Ac 19:35 And after quieting the multitude, the town clerk *said, "Men of Ephesus, what man is there after all who does not know that the city of the Ephesians is guardian of the temple of the great Artemis, and of the [image] which fell down from heaven?
44Ac 19:36 "Since then these are undeniable facts, you ought to keep calm and to do nothing rash.
44Ac 19:37 "For you have brought these men [here] who are neither robbers of temples nor blasphemers of our goddess.
44Ac 19:38 "So then, if Demetrius and the craftsmen who are with him have a complaint against any man, the courts are in session and proconsuls are [available]; let them bring charges against one another.
44Ac 19:39 "But if you want anything beyond this, it shall be settled in the lawful assembly.
44Ac 19:40 "For indeed we are in danger of being accused of a riot in connection with today's affair, since there is no [real] cause [for it]; and in this connection we shall be unable to account for this disorderly gathering."
44Ac 19:41 And after saying this he dismissed the assembly.
44Ac 20:1 And after the uproar had ceased, Paul sent for the disciples and when he had exhorted them and taken his leave of them, he departed to go to Macedonia.
44Ac 20:2 And when he had gone through those districts and had given them much exhortation, he came to Greece.
44Ac 20:3 And [there] he spent three months, and when a plot was formed against him by the Jews as he was about to set sail for Syria, he determined to return through Macedonia.
44Ac 20:4 And he was accompanied by Sopater of Berea, [the son] of Pyrrhus; and by Aristarchus and Secundus of the Thessalonians; and Gaius of Derbe, and Timothy; and Tychicus and Trophimus of Asia.
44Ac 20:5 But these had gone on ahead and were waiting for us at Troas.
44Ac 20:6 And we sailed from Philippi after the days of Unleavened Bread, and came to them at Troas within five days; and there we stayed seven days.
44Ac 20:7 And on the first day of the week, when we were gathered together to break bread, Paul [began] talking to them, intending to depart the next day, and he prolonged his message until midnight.
44Ac 20:8 And there were many lamps in the upper room where we were gathered together.
44Ac 20:9 And there was a certain young man named Eutychus sitting on the window sill, sinking into a deep sleep; and as Paul kept on talking, he was overcome by sleep and fell down from the third floor, and was picked up dead.
44Ac 20:10 But Paul went down and fell upon him and after embracing him, he said, "Do not be troubled, for his life is in him."
44Ac 20:11 And when he had gone [back] up, and had broken the bread and eaten, he talked with them a long while, until daybreak, and so departed.
44Ac 20:12 And they took away the boy alive, and were greatly comforted.
44Ac 20:13 But we, going ahead to the ship, set sail for Assos, intending from there to take Paul on board; for thus he had arranged it, intending himself to go by land.
44Ac 20:14 And when he met us at Assos, we took him on board and came to Mitylene.
44Ac 20:15 And sailing from there, we arrived the following day opposite Chios; and the next day we crossed over to Samos; and the day following we came to Miletus.
44Ac 20:16 For Paul had decided to sail past Ephesus in order that he might not have to spend time in Asia; for he was hurrying to be in Jerusalem, if possible, on the day of Pentecost.
44Ac 20:17 And from Miletus he sent to Ephesus and called to him the elders of the church.
44Ac 20:18 And when they had come to him, he said to them, "You yourselves know, from the first day that I set foot in Asia, how I was with you the whole time,
44Ac 20:19 serving the Lord with all humility and with tears and with trials which came upon me through the plots of the Jews;
44Ac 20:20 how I did not shrink from declaring to you anything that was profitable, and teaching you publicly and from house to house,
44Ac 20:21 solemnly testifying to both Jews and Greeks of repentance toward God and faith in our Lord Jesus Christ.
44Ac 20:22 "And now, behold, bound in spirit, I am on my way to Jerusalem, not knowing what will happen to me there,
44Ac 20:23 except that the Holy Spirit solemnly testifies to me in every city, saying that bonds and afflictions await me.
44Ac 20:24 "But I do not consider my life of any account as dear to myself, in order that I may finish my course, and the ministry which I received from the Lord Jesus, to testify solemnly of the gospel of the grace of God.
44Ac 20:25 "And now, behold, I know that all of you, among whom I went about preaching the kingdom, will see my face no more.
44Ac 20:26 "Therefore I testify to you this day, that I am innocent of the blood of all men.
44Ac 20:27 "For I did not shrink from declaring to you the whole purpose of God.
44Ac 20:28 "Be on guard for yourselves and for all the flock, among which the Holy Spirit has made you overseers, to shepherd the church of God which He purchased with His own blood.
44Ac 20:29 "I know that after my departure savage wolves will come in among you, not sparing the flock;
44Ac 20:30 and from among your own selves men will arise, speaking perverse things, to draw away the disciples after them.
44Ac 20:31 "Therefore be on the alert, remembering that night and day for a period of three years I did not cease to admonish each one with tears.
44Ac 20:32 "And now I commend you to God and to the word of His grace, which is able to build [you] up and to give [you] the inheritance among all those who are sanctified.
44Ac 20:33 "I have coveted no one's silver or gold or clothes.
44Ac 20:34 "You yourselves know that these hands ministered to my [own] needs and to the men who were with me.
44Ac 20:35 "In everything I showed you that by working hard in this manner you must help the weak and remember the words of the Lord Jesus, that He Himself said, 'It is more blessed to give than to receive.'"
44Ac 20:36 And when he had said these things, he knelt down and prayed with them all.
44Ac 20:37 And they [began] to weep aloud and embraced Paul, and repeatedly kissed him,
44Ac 20:38 grieving especially over the word which he had spoken, that they should see his face no more. And they were accompanying him to the ship.
44Ac 21:1 And when it came about that we had parted from them and had set sail, we ran a straight course to Cos and the next day to Rhodes and from there to Patara;
44Ac 21:2 and having found a ship crossing over to Phoenicia, we went aboard and set sail.
44Ac 21:3 And when we had come in sight of Cyprus, leaving it on the left, we kept sailing to Syria and landed at Tyre; for there the ship was to unload its cargo.
44Ac 21:4 And after looking up the disciples, we stayed there seven days; and they kept telling Paul through the Spirit not to set foot in Jerusalem.
44Ac 21:5 And when it came about that our days there were ended, we departed and started on our journey, while they all, with wives and children, escorted us until [we were] out of the city. And after kneeling down on the beach and praying, we said farewell to one another.
44Ac 21:6 Then we went on board the ship, and they returned home again.
44Ac 21:7 And when we had finished the voyage from Tyre, we arrived at Ptolemais; and after greeting the brethren, we stayed with them for a day.
44Ac 21:8 And on the next day we departed and came to Caesarea; and entering the house of Philip the evangelist, who was one of the seven, we stayed with him.
44Ac 21:9 Now this man had four virgin daughters who were prophetesses.
44Ac 21:10 And as we were staying there for some days, a certain prophet named Agabus came down from Judea.
44Ac 21:11 And coming to us, he took Paul's belt and bound his own feet and hands, and said, "This is what the Holy Spirit says： 'In this way the Jews at Jerusalem will bind the man who owns this belt and deliver him into the hands of the Gentiles.'"
44Ac 21:12 And when we had heard this, we as well as the local residents [began] begging him not to go up to Jerusalem.
44Ac 21:13 Then Paul answered, "What are you doing, weeping and breaking my heart? For I am ready not only to be bound, but even to die at Jerusalem for the name of the Lord Jesus."
44Ac 21:14 And since he would not be persuaded, we fell silent, remarking, "The will of the Lord be done!"
44Ac 21:15 And after these days we got ready and started on our way up to Jerusalem.
44Ac 21:16 And [some] of the disciples from Caesarea also came with us, taking us to Mnason of Cyprus, a disciple of long standing with whom we were to lodge.
44Ac 21:17 And when we had come to Jerusalem, the brethren received us gladly.
44Ac 21:18 And now the following day Paul went in with us to James, and all the elders were present.
44Ac 21:19 And after he had greeted them, he [began] to relate one by one the things which God had done among the Gentiles through his ministry.
44Ac 21:20 And when they heard it they [began] glorifying God; and they said to him, "You see, brother, how many thousands there are among the Jews of those who have believed, and they are all zealous for the Law;
44Ac 21:21 and they have been told about you, that you are teaching all the Jews who are among the Gentiles to forsake Moses, telling them not to circumcise their children nor to walk according to the customs.
44Ac 21:22 "What, then, is [to be done]? They will certainly hear that you have come.
44Ac 21:23 "Therefore do this that we tell you. We have four men who are under a vow;
44Ac 21:24 take them and purify yourself along with them, and pay their expenses in order that they may shave their heads; and all will know that there is nothing to the things which they have been told about you, but that you yourself also walk orderly, keeping the Law.
44Ac 21:25 "But concerning the Gentiles who have believed, we wrote, having decided that they should abstain from meat sacrificed to idols and from blood and from what is strangled and from fornication."
44Ac 21:26 Then Paul took the men, and the next day, purifying himself along with them, went into the temple, giving notice of the completion of the days of purification, until the sacrifice was offered for each one of them.
44Ac 21:27 And when the seven days were almost over, the Jews from Asia, upon seeing him in the temple, [began] to stir up all the multitude and laid hands on him,
44Ac 21:28 crying out, "Men of Israel, come to our aid! This is the man who preaches to all men everywhere against our people, and the Law, and this place; and besides he has even brought Greeks into the temple and has defiled this holy place."
44Ac 21:29 For they had previously seen Trophimus the Ephesian in the city with him, and they supposed that Paul had brought him into the temple.
44Ac 21:30 And all the city was aroused, and the people rushed together; and taking hold of Paul, they dragged him out of the temple; and immediately the doors were shut.
44Ac 21:31 And while they were seeking to kill him, a report came up to the commander of the [Roman] cohort that all Jerusalem was in confusion.
44Ac 21:32 And at once he took along [some] soldiers and centurions, and ran down to them; and when they saw the commander and the soldiers, they stopped beating Paul.
44Ac 21:33 Then the commander came up and took hold of him, and ordered him to be bound with two chains; and he [began] asking who he was and what he had done.
44Ac 21:34 But among the crowd some were shouting one thing [and] some another, and when he could not find out the facts on account of the uproar, he ordered him to be brought into the barracks.
44Ac 21:35 And when he got to the stairs, it so happened that he was carried by the soldiers because of the violence of the mob;
44Ac 21:36 for the multitude of the people kept following behind, crying out, " Away with him! "
44Ac 21:37 And as Paul was about to be brought into the barracks, he said to the commander, "May I say something to you?" And he *said, "Do you know Greek?
44Ac 21:38 "Then you are not the Egyptian who some time ago stirred up a revolt and led the four thousand men of the Assassins out into the wilderness?"
44Ac 21:39 But Paul said, "I am a Jew of Tarsus in Cilicia, a citizen of no insignificant city; and I beg you, allow me to speak to the people."
44Ac 21:40 And when he had given him permission, Paul, standing on the stairs, motioned to the people with his hand; and when there was a great hush, he spoke to them in the Hebrew dialect, saying,
44Ac 22:1 "Brethren and fathers, hear my defense which I now [offer] to you."
44Ac 22:2 And when they heard that he was addressing them in the Hebrew dialect, they became even more quiet; and he *said,
44Ac 22:3 "I am a Jew, born in Tarsus of Cilicia, but brought up in this city, educated under Gamaliel, strictly according to the law of our fathers, being zealous for God, just as you all are today.
44Ac 22:4 "And I persecuted this Way to the death, binding and putting both men and women into prisons,
44Ac 22:5 as also the high priest and all the Council of the elders can testify. From them I also received letters to the brethren, and started off for Damascus in order to bring even those who were there to Jerusalem as prisoners to be punished.
44Ac 22:6 "And it came about that as I was on my way, approaching Damascus about noontime, a very bright light suddenly flashed from heaven all around me,
44Ac 22:7 and I fell to the ground and heard a voice saying to me, 'Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting Me?'
44Ac 22:8 "And I answered, 'Who art Thou, Lord?' And He said to me, 'I am Jesus the Nazarene, whom you are persecuting.'
44Ac 22:9 "And those who were with me beheld the light, to be sure, but did not understand the voice of the One who was speaking to me.
44Ac 22:10 "And I said, 'What shall I do, Lord?' And the Lord said to me, 'Arise and go on into Damascus; and there you will be told of all that has been appointed for you to do.'
44Ac 22:11 "But since I could not see because of the brightness of that light, I was led by the hand by those who were with me, and came into Damascus.
44Ac 22:12 "And a certain Ananias, a man who was devout by the standard of the Law, [and] well spoken of by all the Jews who lived there,
44Ac 22:13 came to me, and standing near said to me, 'Brother Saul, receive your sight!' And at that very time I looked up at him.
44Ac 22:14 "And he said, 'The God of our fathers has appointed you to know His will, and to see the Righteous One, and to hear an utterance from His mouth.
44Ac 22:15 'For you will be a witness for Him to all men of what you have seen and heard.
44Ac 22:16 'And now why do you delay? Arise, and be baptized, and wash away your sins, calling on His name.'
44Ac 22:17 "And it came about when I returned to Jerusalem and was praying in the temple, that I fell into a trance,
44Ac 22:18 and I saw Him saying to me, 'Make haste, and get out of Jerusalem quickly, because they will not accept your testimony about Me.'
44Ac 22:19 "And I said, 'Lord, they themselves understand that in one synagogue after another I used to imprison and beat those who believed in Thee.
44Ac 22:20 'And when the blood of Thy witness Stephen was being shed, I also was standing by approving, and watching out for the cloaks of those who were slaying him.'
44Ac 22:21 "And He said to me, 'Go! For I will send you far away to the Gentiles.'"
44Ac 22:22 And they listened to him up to this statement, and [then] they raised their voices and said, "Away with such a fellow from the earth, for he should not be allowed to live!"
44Ac 22:23 And as they were crying out and throwing off their cloaks and tossing dust into the air,
44Ac 22:24 the commander ordered him to be brought into the barracks, stating that he should be examined by scourging so that he might find out the reason why they were shouting against him that way.
44Ac 22:25 And when they stretched him out with thongs, Paul said to the centurion who was standing by, "Is it lawful for you to scourge a man who is a Roman and uncondemned?"
44Ac 22:26 And when the centurion heard [this,] he went to the commander and told him, saying, "What are you about to do? For this man is a Roman."
44Ac 22:27 And the commander came and said to him, "Tell me, are you a Roman?" And he said," Yes. "
44Ac 22:28 And the commander answered, "I acquired this citizenship with a large sum of money." And Paul said, "But I was actually born [a citizen.]"
44Ac 22:29 Therefore those who were about to examine him immediately let go of him; and the commander also was afraid when he found out that he was a Roman, and because he had put him in chains.
44Ac 22:30 But on the next day, wishing to know for certain why he had been accused by the Jews, he released him and ordered the chief priests and all the Council to assemble, and brought Paul down and set him before them.
44Ac 23:1 And Paul, looking intently at the Council, said, "Brethren, I have lived my life with a perfectly good conscience before God up to this day."
44Ac 23:2 And the high priest Ananias commanded those standing beside him to strike him on the mouth.
44Ac 23:3 Then Paul said to him, "God is going to strike you, you whitewashed wall! And do you sit to try me according to the Law, and in violation of the Law order me to be struck?"
44Ac 23:4 But the bystanders said, "Do you revile God's high priest?"
44Ac 23:5 And Paul said, "I was not aware, brethren, that he was high priest; for it is written, 'YOU SHALL NOT SPEAK EVIL OF A RULER OF YOUR PEOPLE.'"
44Ac 23:6 But perceiving that one part were Sadducees and the other Pharisees, Paul [began] crying out in the Council, "Brethren, I am a Pharisee, a son of Pharisees; I am on trial for the hope and resurrection of the dead!"
44Ac 23:7 And as he said this, there arose a dissension between the Pharisees and Sadducees; and the assembly was divided.
44Ac 23:8 For the Sadducees say that there is no resurrection, nor an angel, nor a spirit; but the Pharisees acknowledge them all.
44Ac 23:9 And there arose a great uproar; and some of the scribes of the Pharisaic party stood up and [began] to argue heatedly, saying, "We find nothing wrong with this man; suppose a spirit or an angel has spoken to him?"
44Ac 23:10 And as a great dissension was developing, the commander was afraid Paul would be torn to pieces by them and ordered the troops to go down and take him away from them by force, and bring him into the barracks.
44Ac 23:11 But on the night [immediately] following, the Lord stood at his side and said, "Take courage; for as you have solemnly witnessed to My cause at Jerusalem, so you must witness at Rome also."
44Ac 23:12 And when it was day, the Jews formed a conspiracy and bound themselves under an oath, saying that they would neither eat nor drink until they had killed Paul.
44Ac 23:13 And there were more than forty who formed this plot.
44Ac 23:14 And they came to the chief priests and the elders, and said, "We have bound ourselves under a solemn oath to taste nothing until we have killed Paul.
44Ac 23:15 "Now, therefore, you and the Council notify the commander to bring him down to you, as though you were going to determine his case by a more thorough investigation; and we for our part are ready to slay him before he comes near [the place.]"
44Ac 23:16 But the son of Paul's sister heard of their ambush, and he came and entered the barracks and told Paul.
44Ac 23:17 And Paul called one of the centurions to him and said, "Lead this young man to the commander, for he has something to report to him."
44Ac 23:18 So he took him and led him to the commander and *said, "Paul the prisoner called me to him and asked me to lead this young man to you since he has something to tell you."
44Ac 23:19 And the commander took him by the hand and stepping aside, [began] to inquire of him privately, "What is it that you have to report to me?"
44Ac 23:20 And he said, "The Jews have agreed to ask you to bring Paul down tomorrow to the Council, as though they were going to inquire somewhat more thoroughly about him.
44Ac 23:21 "So do not listen to them, for more than forty of them are lying in wait for him who have bound themselves under a curse not to eat or drink until they slay him; and now they are ready and waiting for the promise from you."
44Ac 23:22 Therefore the commander let the young man go, instructing him, "Tell no one that you have notified me of these things."
44Ac 23:23 And he called to him two of the centurions, and said, "Get two hundred soldiers ready by the third hour of the night to proceed to Caesarea, with seventy horsemen and two hundred spearmen."
44Ac 23:24 [They were] also to provide mounts to put Paul on and bring him safely to Felix the governor.
44Ac 23:25 And he wrote a letter having this form：
44Ac 23:26 "Claudius Lysias, to the most excellent governor Felix, greetings.
44Ac 23:27 "When this man was arrested by the Jews and was about to be slain by them, I came upon them with the troops and rescued him, having learned that he was a Roman.
44Ac 23:28 "And wanting to ascertain the charge for which they were accusing him, I brought him down to their Council;
44Ac 23:29 and I found him to be accused over questions about their Law, but under no accusation deserving death or imprisonment.
44Ac 23:30 "And when I was informed that there would be a plot against the man, I sent him to you at once, also instructing his accusers to bring charges against him before you."
44Ac 23:31 So the soldiers, in accordance with their orders, took Paul and brought him by night to Antipatris.
44Ac 23:32 But the next day, leaving the horsemen to go on with him, they returned to the barracks.
44Ac 23:33 And when these had come to Caesarea and delivered the letter to the governor, they also presented Paul to him.
44Ac 23:34 And when he had read it, he asked from what province he was; and when he learned that he was from Cilicia,
44Ac 23:35 he said, "I will give you a hearing after your accusers arrive also," giving orders for him to be kept in Herod's Praetorium.
44Ac 24:1 And after five days the high priest Ananias came down with some elders, with a certain attorney [named] Tertullus; and they brought charges to the governor against Paul.
44Ac 24:2 And after [Paul] had been summoned, Tertullus began to accuse him, saying [to the governor], "Since we have through you attained much peace, and since by your providence reforms are being carried out for this nation,
44Ac 24:3 we acknowledge [this] in every way and everywhere, most excellent Felix, with all thankfulness.
44Ac 24:4 "But, that I may not weary you any further, I beg you to grant us, by your kindness, a brief hearing.
44Ac 24:5 "For we have found this man a real pest and a fellow who stirs up dissension among all the Jews throughout the world, and a ringleader of the sect of the Nazarenes.
44Ac 24:6 "And he even tried to desecrate the temple; and then we arrested him. {And we wanted to judge him according to our own Law.
44Ac 24:7 "But Lysias the commander came along, and with much violence took him out of our hands,
44Ac 24:8 ordering his accusers to come before you.} And by examining him yourself concerning all these matters, you will be able to ascertain the things of which we accuse him. "
44Ac 24:9 And the Jews also joined in the attack, asserting that these things were so.
44Ac 24:10 And when the governor had nodded for him to speak, Paul responded： "Knowing that for many years you have been a judge to this nation, I cheerfully make my defense,
44Ac 24:11 since you can take note of the fact that no more than twelve days ago I went up to Jerusalem to worship.
44Ac 24:12 "And neither in the temple, nor in the synagogues, nor in the city [itself] did they find me carrying on a discussion with anyone or causing a riot.
44Ac 24:13 "Nor can they prove to you [the charges] of which they now accuse me.
44Ac 24:14 "But this I admit to you, that according to the Way which they call a sect I do serve the God of our fathers, believing everything that is in accordance with the Law, and that is written in the Prophets;
44Ac 24:15 having a hope in God, which these men cherish themselves, that there shall certainly be a resurrection of both the righteous and the wicked.
44Ac 24:16 "In view of this, I also do my best to maintain always a blameless conscience [both] before God and before men.
44Ac 24:17 "Now after several years I came to bring alms to my nation and to present offerings;
44Ac 24:18 in which they found me [occupied] in the temple, having been purified, without [any] crowd or uproar. But [there were] certain Jews from Asia--
44Ac 24:19 who ought to have been present before you, and to make accusation, if they should have anything against me.
44Ac 24:20 "Or else let these men themselves tell what misdeed they found when I stood before the Council,
44Ac 24:21 other than for this one statement which I shouted out while standing among them, 'For the resurrection of the dead I am on trial before you today.' "
44Ac 24:22 But Felix, having a more exact knowledge about the Way, put them off, saying, "When Lysias the commander comes down, I will decide your case."
44Ac 24:23 And he gave orders to the centurion for him to be kept in custody and [yet] have [some] freedom, and not to prevent any of his friends from ministering to him.
44Ac 24:24 But some days later, Felix arrived with Drusilla, his wife who was a Jewess, and sent for Paul, and heard him [speak] about faith in Christ Jesus.
44Ac 24:25 And as he was discussing righteousness, self-control and the judgment to come, Felix became frightened and said, "Go away for the present, and when I find time, I will summon you."
44Ac 24:26 At the same time too, he was hoping that money would be given him by Paul; therefore he also used to send for him quite often and converse with him.
44Ac 24:27 But after two years had passed, Felix was succeeded by Porcius Festus; and wishing to do the Jews a favor, Felix left Paul imprisoned.
44Ac 25:1 Festus therefore, having arrived in the province, three days later went up to Jerusalem from Caesarea.
44Ac 25:2 And the chief priests and the leading men of the Jews brought charges against Paul; and they were urging him,
44Ac 25:3 requesting a concession against Paul, that he might have him brought to Jerusalem ([at the same time,] setting an ambush to kill him on the way).
44Ac 25:4 Festus then answered that Paul was being kept in custody at Caesarea and that he himself was about to leave shortly.
44Ac 25:5 "Therefore," he *said, "let the influential men among you go there with me, and if there is anything wrong about the man, let them prosecute him."
44Ac 25:6 And after he had spent not more than eight or ten days among them, he went down to Caesarea; and on the next day he took his seat on the tribunal and ordered Paul to be brought.
44Ac 25:7 And after he had arrived, the Jews who had come down from Jerusalem stood around him, bringing many and serious charges against him which they could not prove;
44Ac 25:8 while Paul said in his own defense, "I have committed no offense either against the Law of the Jews or against the temple or against Caesar."
44Ac 25:9 But Festus, wishing to do the Jews a favor, answered Paul and said, " Are you willing to go up to Jerusalem and stand trial before me on these [ charges]? "
44Ac 25:10 But Paul said, "I am standing before Caesar's tribunal, where I ought to be tried. I have done no wrong to [the] Jews, as you also very well know.
44Ac 25:11 "If then I am a wrongdoer, and have committed anything worthy of death, I do not refuse to die; but if none of those things is [true] of which these men accuse me, no one can hand me over to them. I appeal to Caesar."
44Ac 25:12 Then when Festus had conferred with his council, he answered, "You have appealed to Caesar, to Caesar you shall go."
44Ac 25:13 Now when several days had elapsed, King Agrippa and Bernice arrived at Caesarea, and paid their respects to Festus.
44Ac 25:14 And while they were spending many days there, Festus laid Paul's case before the king, saying, "There is a certain man left a prisoner by Felix;
44Ac 25:15 and when I was at Jerusalem, the chief priests and the elders of the Jews brought charges against him, asking for a sentence of condemnation upon him.
44Ac 25:16 "And I answered them that it is not the custom of the Romans to hand over any man before the accused meets his accusers face to face, and has an opportunity to make his defense against the charges.
44Ac 25:17 "And so after they had assembled here, I made no delay, but on the next day took my seat on the tribunal, and ordered the man to be brought.
44Ac 25:18 "And when the accusers stood up, they [began] bringing charges against him not of such crimes as I was expecting;
44Ac 25:19 but they [simply] had some points of disagreement with him about their own religion and about a certain dead man, Jesus, whom Paul asserted to be alive.
44Ac 25:20 "And being at a loss how to investigate such matters, I asked whether he was willing to go to Jerusalem and there stand trial on these matters.
44Ac 25:21 "But when Paul appealed to be held in custody for the Emperor's decision, I ordered him to be kept in custody until I send him to Caesar."
44Ac 25:22 And Agrippa [said] to Festus, "I also would like to hear the man myself." "Tomorrow," he *said, "you shall hear him."
44Ac 25:23 And so, on the next day when Agrippa had come together with Bernice, amid great pomp, and had entered the auditorium accompanied by the commanders and the prominent men of the city, at the command of Festus, Paul was brought in.
44Ac 25:24 And Festus *said, "King Agrippa, and all you gentlemen here present with us, you behold this man about whom all the people of the Jews appealed to me, both at Jerusalem and here, loudly declaring that he ought not to live any longer.
44Ac 25:25 "But I found that he had committed nothing worthy of death; and since he himself appealed to the Emperor, I decided to send him.
44Ac 25:26 "Yet I have nothing definite about him to write to my lord. Therefore I have brought him before you [all] and especially before you, King Agrippa, so that after the investigation has taken place, I may have something to write.
44Ac 25:27 "For it seems absurd to me in sending a prisoner, not to indicate also the charges against him."
44Ac 26:1 And Agrippa said to Paul, "You are permitted to speak for yourself." Then Paul stretched out his hand and [proceeded] to make his defense：
44Ac 26:2 "In regard to all the things of which I am accused by the Jews, I consider myself fortunate, King Agrippa, that I am about to make my defense before you today;
44Ac 26:3 especially because you are an expert in all customs and questions among [the] Jews; therefore I beg you to listen to me patiently.
44Ac 26:4 "So then, all Jews know my manner of life from my youth up, which from the beginning was spent among my [own] nation and at Jerusalem;
44Ac 26:5 since they have known about me for a long time previously, if they are willing to testify, that I lived [as] a Pharisee according to the strictest sect of our religion.
44Ac 26:6 "And now I am standing trial for the hope of the promise made by God to our fathers;
44Ac 26:7 [the promise] to which our twelve tribes hope to attain, as they earnestly serve [God] night and day. And for this hope, O King, I am being accused by Jews.
44Ac 26:8 "Why is it considered incredible among you [people] if God does raise the dead?
44Ac 26:9 "So then, I thought to myself that I had to do many things hostile to the name of Jesus of Nazareth.
44Ac 26:10 "And this is just what I did in Jerusalem; not only did I lock up many of the saints in prisons, having received authority from the chief priests, but also when they were being put to death I cast my vote against them.
44Ac 26:11 "And as I punished them often in all the synagogues, I tried to force them to blaspheme; and being furiously enraged at them, I kept pursuing them even to foreign cities.
44Ac 26:12 "While thus engaged as I was journeying to Damascus with the authority and commission of the chief priests,
44Ac 26:13 at midday, O King, I saw on the way a light from heaven, brighter than the sun, shining all around me and those who were journeying with me.
44Ac 26:14 "And when we had all fallen to the ground, I heard a voice saying to me in the Hebrew dialect, 'Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting Me? It is hard for you to kick against the goads.'
44Ac 26:15 "And I said, 'Who art Thou, Lord?' And the Lord said, 'I am Jesus whom you are persecuting.
44Ac 26:16 'But arise, and stand on your feet; for this purpose I have appeared to you, to appoint you a minister and a witness not only to the things which you have seen, but also to the things in which I will appear to you;
44Ac 26:17 delivering you from the [Jewish] people and from the Gentiles, to whom I am sending you,
44Ac 26:18 to open their eyes so that they may turn from darkness to light and from the dominion of Satan to God, in order that they may receive forgiveness of sins and an inheritance among those who have been sanctified by faith in Me. '
44Ac 26:19 "Consequently, King Agrippa, I did not prove disobedient to the heavenly vision,
44Ac 26:20 but [kept] declaring both to those of Damascus first, and [also] at Jerusalem and [then] throughout all the region of Judea, and [even] to the Gentiles, that they should repent and turn to God, performing deeds appropriate to repentance.
44Ac 26:21 "For this reason [some] Jews seized me in the temple and tried to put me to death.
44Ac 26:22 "And so, having obtained help from God, I stand to this day testifying both to small and great, stating nothing but what the Prophets and Moses said was going to take place;
44Ac 26:23 that the Christ was to suffer, [and] that by reason of [His] resurrection from the dead He should be the first to proclaim light both to the [Jewish] people and to the Gentiles. "
44Ac 26:24 And while [Paul] was saying this in his defense, Festus *said in a loud voice, "Paul, you are out of your mind! [Your] great learning is driving you mad."
44Ac 26:25 But Paul *said, "I am not out of my mind, most excellent Festus, but I utter words of sober truth.
44Ac 26:26 "For the king knows about these matters, and I speak to him also with confidence, since I am persuaded that none of these things escape his notice; for this has not been done in a corner.
44Ac 26:27 "King Agrippa, do you believe the Prophets? I know that you do."
44Ac 26:28 And Agrippa [replied] to Paul, "In a short time you will persuade me to become a Christian."
44Ac 26:29 And Paul [said,] "I would to God, that whether in a short or long time, not only you, but also all who hear me this day, might become such as I am, except for these chains."
44Ac 26:30 And the king arose and the governor and Bernice, and those who were sitting with them,
44Ac 26:31 and when they had drawn aside, they [began] talking to one another, saying, "This man is not doing anything worthy of death or imprisonment."
44Ac 26:32 And Agrippa said to Festus, "This man might have been set free if he had not appealed to Caesar."
44Ac 27:1 And when it was decided that we should sail for Italy, they proceeded to deliver Paul and some other prisoners to a centurion of the Augustan cohort named Julius.
44Ac 27:2 And embarking in an Adramyttian ship, which was about to sail to the regions along the coast of Asia, we put out to sea, accompanied by Aristarchus, a Macedonian of Thessalonica.
44Ac 27:3 And the next day we put in at Sidon; and Julius treated Paul with consideration and allowed him to go to his friends and receive care.
44Ac 27:4 And from there we put out to sea and sailed under the shelter of Cyprus because the winds were contrary.
44Ac 27:5 And when we had sailed through the sea along the coast of Cilicia and Pamphylia, we landed at Myra in Lycia.
44Ac 27:6 And there the centurion found an Alexandrian ship sailing for Italy, and he put us aboard it.
44Ac 27:7 And when we had sailed slowly for a good many days, and with difficulty had arrived off Cnidus, since the wind did not permit us [to go] farther, we sailed under the shelter of Crete, off Salmone;
44Ac 27:8 and with difficulty sailing past it we came to a certain place called Fair Havens, near which was the city of Lasea.
44Ac 27:9 And when considerable time had passed and the voyage was now dangerous, since even the fast was already over, Paul [began] to admonish them,
44Ac 27:10 and said to them, "Men, I perceive that the voyage will certainly be [attended] with damage and great loss, not only of the cargo and the ship, but also of our lives."
44Ac 27:11 But the centurion was more persuaded by the pilot and the captain of the ship, than by what was being said by Paul.
44Ac 27:12 And because the harbor was not suitable for wintering, the majority reached a decision to put out to sea from there, if somehow they could reach Phoenix, a harbor of Crete, facing southwest and northwest, and spend the winter [there.]
44Ac 27:13 And when a moderate south wind came up, supposing that they had gained their purpose, they weighed anchor and [began] sailing along Crete, close [inshore.]
44Ac 27:14 But before very long there rushed down from the land a violent wind, called Euraquilo;
44Ac 27:15 and when the ship was caught [in it,] and could not face the wind, we gave way [to it,] and let ourselves be driven along.
44Ac 27:16 And running under the shelter of a small island called Clauda, we were scarcely able to get the [ship's] boat under control.
44Ac 27:17 And after they had hoisted it up, they used supporting cables in undergirding the ship; and fearing that they might run aground on [the shallows] of Syrtis, they let down the sea anchor, and so let themselves be driven along.
44Ac 27:18 The next day as we were being violently storm-tossed, they began to jettison the cargo;
44Ac 27:19 and on the third day they threw the ship's tackle overboard with their own hands.
44Ac 27:20 And since neither sun nor stars appeared for many days, and no small storm was assailing [us,] from then on all hope of our being saved was gradually abandoned.
44Ac 27:21 And when they had gone a long time without food, then Paul stood up in their midst and said, "Men, you ought to have followed my advice and not to have set sail from Crete, and incurred this damage and loss.
44Ac 27:22 "And [yet] now I urge you to keep up your courage, for there shall be no loss of life among you, but [only] of the ship.
44Ac 27:23 "For this very night an angel of the God to whom I belong and whom I serve stood before me,
44Ac 27:24 saying, 'Do not be afraid, Paul; you must stand before Caesar; and behold, God has granted you all those who are sailing with you.'
44Ac 27:25 "Therefore, keep up your courage, men, for I believe God, that it will turn out exactly as I have been told.
44Ac 27:26 "But we must run aground on a certain island."
44Ac 27:27 But when the fourteenth night had come, as we were being driven about in the Adriatic Sea, about midnight the sailors [began] to surmise that they were approaching some land.
44Ac 27:28 And they took soundings, and found [it to be] twenty fathoms; and a little farther on they took another sounding and found [it to be] fifteen fathoms.
44Ac 27:29 And fearing that we might run aground somewhere on the rocks, they cast four anchors from the stern and wished for daybreak.
44Ac 27:30 And as the sailors were trying to escape from the ship, and had let down the [ship's] boat into the sea, on the pretense of intending to lay out anchors from the bow,
44Ac 27:31 Paul said to the centurion and to the soldiers, "Unless these men remain in the ship, you yourselves cannot be saved."
44Ac 27:32 Then the soldiers cut away the ropes of the [ship's] boat, and let it fall away.
44Ac 27:33 And until the day was about to dawn, Paul was encouraging them all to take some food, saying, "Today is the fourteenth day that you have been constantly watching and going without eating, having taken nothing.
44Ac 27:34 "Therefore I encourage you to take some food, for this is for your preservation; for not a hair from the head of any of you shall perish."
44Ac 27:35 And having said this, he took bread and gave thanks to God in the presence of all; and he broke it and began to eat.
44Ac 27:36 And all of them were encouraged, and they themselves also took food.
44Ac 27:37 And all of us in the ship were two hundred and seventy-six persons.
44Ac 27:38 And when they had eaten enough, they [began] to lighten the ship by throwing out the wheat into the sea.
44Ac 27:39 And when day came, they could not recognize the land; but they did observe a certain bay with a beach, and they resolved to drive the ship onto it if they could.
44Ac 27:40 And casting off the anchors, they left them in the sea while at the same time they were loosening the ropes of the rudders, and hoisting the foresail to the wind, they were heading for the beach.
44Ac 27:41 But striking a reef where two seas met, they ran the vessel aground; and the prow stuck fast and remained immovable, but the stern [began] to be broken up by the force [of the waves.]
44Ac 27:42 And the soldiers' plan was to kill the prisoners, that none [of them] should swim away and escape;
44Ac 27:43 but the centurion, wanting to bring Paul safely through, kept them from their intention, and commanded that those who could swim should jump overboard first and get to land,
44Ac 27:44 and the rest [should follow], some on planks, and others on various things from the ship. And thus it happened that they all were brought safely to land.
44Ac 28:1 And when they had been brought safely through, then we found out that the island was called Malta.
44Ac 28:2 And the natives showed us extraordinary kindness; for because of the rain that had set in and because of the cold, they kindled a fire and received us all.
44Ac 28:3 But when Paul had gathered a bundle of sticks and laid them on the fire, a viper came out because of the heat, and fastened on his hand.
44Ac 28:4 And when the natives saw the creature hanging from his hand, they [ began] saying to one another, "Undoubtedly this man is a murderer, and though he has been saved from the sea, justice has not allowed him to live."
44Ac 28:5 However he shook the creature off into the fire and suffered no harm.
44Ac 28:6 But they were expecting that he was about to swell up or suddenly fall down dead. But after they had waited a long time and had seen nothing unusual happen to him, they changed their minds and [began] to say that he was a god.
44Ac 28:7 Now in the neighborhood of that place were lands belonging to the leading man of the island, named Publius, who welcomed us and entertained us courteously three days.
44Ac 28:8 And it came about that the father of Publius was lying [in bed] afflicted with [recurrent] fever and dysentery; and Paul went in [to see] him and after he had prayed, he laid his hands on him and healed him.
44Ac 28:9 And after this had happened, the rest of the people on the island who had diseases were coming to him and getting cured.
44Ac 28:10 And they also honored us with many marks of respect; and when we were setting sail, they supplied [us] with all we needed.
44Ac 28:11 And at the end of three months we set sail on an Alexandrian ship which had wintered at the island, and which had the Twin Brothers for its figurehead.
44Ac 28:12 And after we put in at Syracuse, we stayed there for three days.
44Ac 28:13 And from there we sailed around and arrived at Rhegium, and a day later a south wind sprang up, and on the second day we came to Puteoli.
44Ac 28:14 There we found [some] brethren, and were invited to stay with them for seven days; and thus we came to Rome.
44Ac 28:15 And the brethren, when they heard about us, came from there as far as the Market of Appius and Three Inns to meet us; and when Paul saw them, he thanked God and took courage.
44Ac 28:16 And when we entered Rome, Paul was allowed to stay by himself, with the soldier who was guarding him.
44Ac 28:17 And it happened that after three days he called together those who were the leading men of the Jews, and when they had come together, he [began] saying to them, "Brethren, though I had done nothing against our people, or the customs of our fathers, yet I was delivered prisoner from Jerusalem into the hands of the Romans.
44Ac 28:18 "And when they had examined me, they were willing to release me because there was no ground for putting me to death.
44Ac 28:19 "But when the Jews objected, I was forced to appeal to Caesar; not that I had any accusation against my nation.
44Ac 28:20 "For this reason therefore, I requested to see you and to speak with you, for I am wearing this chain for the sake of the hope of Israel."
44Ac 28:21 And they said to him, "We have neither received letters from Judea concerning you, nor have any of the brethren come here and reported or spoken anything bad about you.
44Ac 28:22 "But we desire to hear from you what your views are; for concerning this sect, it is known to us that it is spoken against everywhere."
44Ac 28:23 And when they had set a day for him, they came to him at his lodging in large numbers; and he was explaining to them by solemnly testifying about the kingdom of God, and trying to persuade them concerning Jesus, from both the Law of Moses and from the Prophets, from morning until evening.
44Ac 28:24 And some were being persuaded by the things spoken, but others would not believe.
44Ac 28:25 And when they did not agree with one another, they [began] leaving after Paul had spoken one [parting] word, "The Holy Spirit rightly spoke through Isaiah the prophet to your fathers,
44Ac 28:26 saying, 'GO TO THIS PEOPLE AND SAY, "YOU WILL KEEP ON HEARING, BUT WILL NOT UNDERSTAND; AND YOU WILL KEEP ON SEEING, BUT WILL NOT PERCEIVE;
44Ac 28:27 FOR THE HEART OF THIS PEOPLE HAS BECOME DULL, AND WITH THEIR EARS THEY SCARCELY HEAR, AND THEY HAVE CLOSED THEIR EYES; LEST THEY SHOULD SEE WITH THEIR EYES, AND HEAR WITH THEIR EARS, AND UNDERSTAND WITH THEIR HEART AND RETURN, AND I SHOULD HEAL THEM. "'
44Ac 28:28 "Let it be known to you therefore, that this salvation of God has been sent to the Gentiles; they will also listen."
44Ac 28:29 {And when he had spoken these words, the Jews departed, having a great dispute among themselves.}
44Ac 28:30 And he stayed two full years in his own rented quarters, and was welcoming all who came to him,
44Ac 28:31 preaching the kingdom of God, and teaching concerning the Lord Jesus Christ with all openness, unhindered.
